}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gandhi, Indira}}\n[[Category:Indira Gandhi|*]]\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:4th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:Assassinated heads of government]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bandung Conference attendees]]\n[[Category:Children of Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:People from Raebareli]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in India]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Female defence ministers]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:People associated with Santiniketan]]\n[[Category:Indian socialists]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:Lenin Peace Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Ministers for External Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Information and Broadcasting of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Nehru\u2013Gandhi family]]\n[[Category:People educated at Badminton School]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Delhi]]\n[[Category:People of the Emergency (India)]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Cabinet of India]]\n[[Category:Women leaders of India]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Lok Sabha]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Victims of Sikh terrorism]]\n[[Category:Assassination of Indira Gandhi]]\n[[Category:5th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:6th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:7th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEconomic policy:added citation; wording; added WP links; edits for flow; fixed fonts, punctuation; rem duplicate WP links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indira_Gandhi"}
{"title_page": "Sonallah Ibrahim", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Sonallah Ibrahim\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            =\n| native_name        = '''\u0635\u0646\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645''' \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date = \n| nationality        = [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] {{flag icon|Egypt}}\n| other_names        = \n| education          =  \n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n|website             = \n}}\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:Son'allah Ibrahim.jpg|thumb]] -->\n'''Son'allah Ibrahim''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0635\u0646\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645</big>}} ''\u1e62un\u02bb All\u0101h Ibr\u0101h\u012bm'') (born 1937) is an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] [[novelist]] and [[short story]] writer and one of the \"[[Sixties Generation]]\" who is known for his [[Left-wing politics|leftist]] and nationalist views which are expressed rather directly in his work. His novels, especially later ones, incorporate many excerpts from newspapers, magazines and other political sources as a way to enlighten the people about a certain political or social issue. Because of his political opinions he was imprisoned during the 1960s; his imprisonment is featured in his first book, ''That Smell'' (\u062a\u0644\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0626\u062d\u0629), which was one of the first writings in [[Egyptian literature]] to adopt a modernist tinge.\n\nIn harmony with his political ideas, in 2003 he refused to accept a prestigious literary award worth 100,000 [[Egyptian pound]]s from Egypt's [[Ministry of Culture (Egypt)|Ministry of Culture]].\n\n==Life==\n\nSonallah Ibrahim was born in [[Cairo]]. His father was an upper-middle class civil servant; his mother, from a poor background, had been a nurse hired to look after his father's paralysed first wife. Ibrahim entered [[Cairo University]] to study law in 1952.<ref name=\"Hassan2003\">Abdalla F. Hassan, [http://www.worldpress.org/Mideast/1205.cfm Black Humor in Dark Times], 19 June 2003.</ref> There he joined the Marxist [[Democratic Movement for National Liberation]] (DMNL). Despite the DMNL's support for [[Nasser]]'s coup, Nasser moved to repress Communists in the late 1950s.<ref name=\"Schatz2013\">Adam Schatz, Black, not Noir [review of Ibrahim, trans. Robyn Creswell, '' 'That Smell' and 'Notes from Prison' ''], ''[[London Review of Books]]'' Vol. 35 No. 5 (7 March 2013), pp.15-16.</ref> Ibrahim, arrested in 1959, received a seven-year prison sentence from a military tribunal.<ref name=\"Hassan2003\"/> He was released in 1964 on the occasion of [[Nikita Khrushchev]] visiting Egypt for the opening of the [[Aswan Dam]].<ref name=\"Schatz2013\"/>\n\n==Writings==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2014}}\nHosam Aboul-Ela of the [[University of Houston]] described Ibrahim as \"a relentless internal critic of successive Egyptian regimes\" and wrote that \"Ibrahim might best be described as a sort of Egyptian cross between [[Jonathan Swift]] and [[Manuel Puig]]\".<ref name=Aboul-Elap251>Aboul-Ela, p. 251.</ref>\n\nHis novels are typically told in the first person, in a cold objective tone resembling press reportage which mimics reality. His main theme seems to be the importance of resisting the influence of the political mega-powers which attempt to invade the third world economically through many ways including the transcontinental companies. As an example, \"Sharaf\" [=Honour] deals with the intrusion of American politics in Egypt and includes long passages frankly criticising the big drug companies and their policies in third world countries. His interests are not limited to the situation in Egypt; \"Beirut..Beirut\" is something like an overview of the Lebanese civil war of the '70s and '80s, and \"Warda\" reveals a little-known episode about the activities of leftists and communists in Yemen and Oman in the '60s and '70s. The title of one of his latest novels is \"Amricanly\" which superficially means \" American\" or \"in an American way\" but is really a parody of another word \"Othmanly\" related to the notorious Dark Ages when Turkey ruled Egypt. The word \"Amricanly\" in another way is almost a transliteration of the phrase \"My affairs '''''were''''' mine\" in Arabic. His novel, \"The Committee\" is often described by critics as [[kafkaesque]]. In it the protagonist seeks entry into a shadowy organization. He is routinely subject to their vetting process and Sonallah uses his character to make numerous political observations in the form of speeches to the committee.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nSeveral of Ibrahim's works also explore how repetition and fastidious attention to detail can be used to examine the themes of childhood innocence, boredom, and sexual frustration. In ''Stealth'', the narrator recounts his childhood memories living with his father in a small, modest apartment. By describing each part of a mundane action, such as hanging up a coat or cooking some eggs, the narrator conveys his childhood curiosity and naivete about the adult world around him. In ''Ice'', extensive repetition of intimate acts, with the same atomistic attention to detail, indicates the narrator's boredom and frustration with life as a foreign student in Soviet Russia.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Works==\n\n*''The Smell of It'' (\u062a\u0644\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0626\u062d\u0629) (1966)\n**Translated by [[Denys Johnson Davies|Denys Johnson-Davies]], 1971; retranslated as ''That Smell & Notes from Prison'', [[Robyn Creswell]], 2013\n**This ''[[roman \u00e0 clef]]'' novella, set during the rule of [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]], is about a young Egyptian writer who had been a political prisoner is released, and he takes a look at the street life in his country.<ref name=\"Aboul-Elap2512\" />\n*''The Star of August'' (\u0646\u062c\u0645\u0629 \u0623\u063a\u0633\u0637\u0633) (1974)\n*''[[The Committee (novel)|The Committee]]'' (\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629) (1981)\n** Translated by [[Charlene Constable]] and [[Mary St Germain]], 2001, published by [[Syracuse University Press]]<ref name=\"Aboul-Elap2512\" />\n*''Beirut..Beirut'' (\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a) (1984)\n**Translated by Chip Rossetti, 2014, published by [[Bloomsbury Qatar Foundation Publishing]].\n* ''[[Zaat (novel)|Zaat]]'' (\u0630\u0627\u062a) (1992)\n**Translated by [[Anthony Calderbank]], 2001\n* ''Honor''  (\u0634\u0631\u0641) (1997)\n*''Cairo from Edge to Edge'' (1998)\n**A portrait of Cairo with photographer Jean Pierre Ribiere\n*''Rose''  (\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0629) (2000)\n* ''Amricanly''  (\u0623\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0643\u0627\u0646\u0644\u0649) (2003)\n* ''Memoirs from the Oasis Prison'' (\u064a\u0648\u0645\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0627\u062d\u0627\u062a) (2005)\n* ''Stealth''  (\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0635\u0635) (2007)\n**Translated by [[Hosam Aboul-Ela]], 2010\n* ''The Turban and the Cap''  (\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0628\u0639\u0629) (2008)\n* ''Ice'' (\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0644\u064a\u062f) (2011)\n\n'''As a translator'''\n\n* \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062f\u0648 (The Enemy) by [[James William Drought]]\n\n==Awards==\n*The [[Ibn Rushd Prize for Freedom of Thought]] for the year 2004 in Berlin.\n\n==References==\n* Aboul-Ela, Hosam ([[University of Houston]]). \"Book Reviews.\" ''[[Edebiy\u00e2t]]'', 2003, Vol. 13, No. 2, pp.&nbsp;251\u2013268 (relevant pages: 251-253). ISSN 0364-6505 print; ISSN 1477-2841 online/02/020251-18. [[Taylor & Francis Ltd]], DOI: 10.1080/0364650032000143283.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060209035924/http://kefaya.org/reports/0311Alkhamisi.htm Son'allah Ibrahim refusing a prize] {{in lang|ar}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061201084427/http://adab.chez-alice.fr/index.php?page=sonallah.htm Sonallah Ibrahim bio-bibliography] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibrahim, Sonallah}}\n[[Category:Arab communists]]\n[[Category:Egyptian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Sonallah Ibrahim\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            =\n| native_name        = '''\u0635\u0646\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645''' \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date = \n| nationality        = [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] {{flag icon|Egypt}}\n| other_names        = \n| education          =  \n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n|website             = \n}}\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:Son'allah Ibrahim.jpg|thumb]] -->\n'''Son'allah Ibrahim''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0635\u0646\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645</big>}} ''\u1e62un\u02bb All\u0101h Ibr\u0101h\u012bm'') (born 1937) is an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] [[novelist]] and [[short story]] writer and one of the \"[[Sixties Generation]]\" who is known for his [[Left-wing politics|leftist]] and nationalist views which are expressed rather directly in his work. His novels, especially later ones, incorporate many excerpts from newspapers, magazines and other political sources as a way to enlighten the people about a certain political or social issue. Because of his political opinions he was imprisoned during the 1960s; his imprisonment is featured in his first book, ''That Smell'' (\u062a\u0644\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0626\u062d\u0629), which was one of the first writings in [[Egyptian literature]] to adopt a modernist tinge.\n\nIn harmony with his political ideas, in 2003 he refused to accept a prestigious literary award worth 100,000 [[Egyptian pound]]s from Egypt's [[Ministry of Culture (Egypt)|Ministry of Culture]].\n\n==Life==\n\nSonallah Ibrahim was born in [[Cairo]]. His father was an upper-middle class civil servant; his mother, from a poor background, had been a nurse hired to look after his father's paralysed first wife. Ibrahim entered [[Cairo University]] to study law in 1952.<ref name=\"Hassan2003\">Abdalla F. Hassan, [http://www.worldpress.org/Mideast/1205.cfm Black Humor in Dark Times], 19 June 2003.</ref> There he joined the Marxist [[Democratic Movement for National Liberation]] (DMNL). Despite the DMNL's support for [[Nasser]]'s coup, Nasser moved to repress Communists in the late 1950s.<ref name=\"Schatz2013\">Adam Schatz, Black, not Noir [review of Ibrahim, trans. Robyn Creswell, '' 'That Smell' and 'Notes from Prison' ''], ''[[London Review of Books]]'' Vol. 35 No. 5 (7 March 2013), pp.15-16.</ref> Ibrahim, arrested in 1959, received a seven-year prison sentence from a military tribunal.<ref name=\"Hassan2003\"/> He was released in 1964 on the occasion of [[Nikita Khrushchev]] visiting Egypt for the opening of the [[Aswan Dam]].<ref name=\"Schatz2013\"/>\n\n==Writings==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2014}}\nHosam Aboul-Ela of the [[University of Houston]] described Ibrahim as \"a relentless internal critic of successive Egyptian regimes\" and wrote that \"Ibrahim might best be described as a sort of Egyptian cross between [[Jonathan Swift]] and [[Manuel Puig]]\".<ref name=Aboul-Elap251>Aboul-Ela, p. 251.</ref>\n\nHis novels are typically told in the first person, in a cold objective tone resembling press reportage which mimics reality. His main theme seems to be the importance of resisting the influence of the political mega-powers which attempt to invade the third world economically through many ways including the transcontinental companies. As an example, \"Sharaf\" [=Honour] deals with the intrusion of American politics in Egypt and includes long passages frankly criticising the big drug companies and their policies in third world countries. His interests are not limited to the situation in Egypt; \"Beirut..Beirut\" is something like an overview of the Lebanese civil war of the '70s and '80s, and \"Warda\" reveals a little-known episode about the activities of leftists and communists in Yemen and Oman in the '60s and '70s. The title of one of his latest novels is \"Amricanly\" which superficially means \" American\" or \"in an American way\" but is really a parody of another word \"Othmanly\" related to the notorious Dark Ages when Turkey ruled Egypt. The word \"Amricanly\" in another way is almost a transliteration of the phrase \"My affairs '''''were''''' mine\" in Arabic. His novel, \"The Committee\" is often described by critics as [[kafkaesque]]. In it the protagonist seeks entry into a shadowy organization. He is routinely subject to their vetting process and Sonallah uses his character to make numerous political observations in the form of speeches to the committee.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nSeveral of Ibrahim's works also explore how repetition and fastidious attention to detail can be used to examine the themes of childhood innocence, boredom, and sexual frustration. In ''Stealth'', the narrator recounts his childhood memories living with his father in a small, modest apartment. By describing each part of a mundane action, such as hanging up a coat or cooking some eggs, the narrator conveys his childhood curiosity and naivete about the adult world around him. In ''Ice'', extensive repetition of intimate acts, with the same atomistic attention to detail, indicates the narrator's boredom and frustration with life as a foreign student in Soviet Russia.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Works==\n\n*''The Smell of It'' (\u062a\u0644\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0626\u062d\u0629) (1966)\n**Translated by [[Denys Johnson Davies]], 1971; retranslated as ''That Smell & Notes from Prison'', [[Robyn Creswell]], 2013\n**This ''[[roman \u00e0 clef]]'' novella, set during the rule of [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]], is about a young Egyptian writer who had been a political prisoner is released, and he takes a look at the street life in his country.<ref name=\"Aboul-Elap2512\" />\n*''The Star of August'' (\u0646\u062c\u0645\u0629 \u0623\u063a\u0633\u0637\u0633) (1974)\n*''[[The Committee (novel)|The Committee]]'' (\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629) (1981)\n** Translated by [[Charlene Constable]] and [[Mary St Germain]], 2001, published by [[Syracuse University Press]]<ref name=\"Aboul-Elap2512\" />\n*''Beirut..Beirut'' (\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a) (1984)\n**Translated by Chip Rossetti, 2014, published by [[Bloomsbury Qatar Foundation Publishing]].\n* ''[[Zaat (novel)|Zaat]]'' (\u0630\u0627\u062a) (1992)\n**Translated by [[Anthony Calderbank]], 2001\n* ''Honor''  (\u0634\u0631\u0641) (1997)\n*''Cairo from Edge to Edge'' (1998)\n**A portrait of Cairo with photographer Jean Pierre Ribiere\n*''Rose''  (\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0629) (2000)\n* ''Amricanly''  (\u0623\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0643\u0627\u0646\u0644\u0649) (2003)\n* ''Memoirs from the Oasis Prison'' (\u064a\u0648\u0645\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0627\u062d\u0627\u062a) (2005)\n* ''Stealth''  (\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0635\u0635) (2007)\n**Translated by [[Hosam Aboul-Ela]], 2010\n* ''The Turban and the Cap''  (\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0628\u0639\u0629) (2008)\n* ''Ice'' (\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0644\u064a\u062f) (2011)\n\n'''Work as a translator'''\n\n* \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062f\u0648 (The Enemy) by [[James William Drought]]\n\n==Awards==\n*The [[Ibn Rushd Prize for Freedom of Thought]] for the year 2004 in Berlin.\n\n==References==\n* Aboul-Ela, Hosam ([[University of Houston]]). \"Book Reviews.\" ''[[Edebiy\u00e2t]]'', 2003, Vol. 13, No. 2, pp.&nbsp;251\u2013268 (relevant pages: 251-253). ISSN 0364-6505 print; ISSN 1477-2841 online/02/020251-18. [[Taylor & Francis Ltd]], DOI: 10.1080/0364650032000143283.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060209035924/http://kefaya.org/reports/0311Alkhamisi.htm Son'allah Ibrahim refusing a prize] {{in lang|ar}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061201084427/http://adab.chez-alice.fr/index.php?page=sonallah.htm Sonallah Ibrahim bio-bibliography] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibrahim, Sonallah}}\n[[Category:Arab communists]]\n[[Category:Egyptian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n", "name_user": "MichelCastagne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonallah_Ibrahim"}
{"title_page": "Wilkanowski", "text_new": "(Wladyslaw)<ref name=\"heritage\">[https://www.myheritage.es/names/natalie_wilkanowski] Parents of Natalie Wilkanowski</ref> '''William \"Willi\" Wilkanowski''' (born November 15, [[1886]]<ref name=\"grave\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/171555966/william-wilkanowski] Grave of William Wilkanowski Grave with DOB and date of interring</ref> in [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144]],<ref name=\"draft1942\">U.S. World War II Draft Registration Cards, 1942</ref> [[Poland]], dead December 8, [[1954]] in Long Island, USA)<ref name=\"obituary\">[https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52894684/?terms=wilkanowski] William Wilkanowski Obituary, The Brooklyn Daily Eagle, December 11, 1954</ref> was a [[Polish-American]] [[violin]]-maker, [[guitar]]-maker and violinist. He was a very productive [[luthier]], known for making over 5000 violins and 100 violas with his staff at his workshop.<ref name=\"Fairfield\">Fairfield, John H. (1942) ''Known Violin Makers''. Virtuoso Pubns Inc. {{ISBN|0-918624-00-2}}</ref> He also created 30 unique, high-end archtop guitars, one of which, the Wilkanowski Airway W-4, was famously owned by [[Johnny Cash]] since the 1980s.<ref name=\"Cash\">[https://www.retrofret.com/product.asp?ProductID=4172] Wilkanowski Airway W-4 owned by Cash, listed as auction item</ref>\n\nWilkanowski was also known to be a family man, marrying early to his wife Amelia (1885/1886 - May 10, 1952),<ref name=\"graveWife\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/171555967/amelia-wilkanowski] Grave of Amelia Wilkanowski</ref> with whom he had raised 9 children. When Amelia got sick, in 1950 he sold his shop property and moved his workshop to their Long Island home to be close to her and look after her. After she died of the illness in 1952, he became very depressed and despondent without her.<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref> He stopped making instruments altogether and lost his source of income, which negatively affected his finances, adding to his depressive state.<ref name=\"Cozio Archive\">William Wilkanowski biography article by Ira Kraemer in the Cozio Archive</ref> In early December 1954, he finally committed suicide<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref> and was laid to rest next to Amelia on December 13, 1954.<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref><ref name=\"grave\"></ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWilkanowski was born on November 15, 1886 as listed on his grave and in the draft card, and the year 1886 indicated as estimated in several census records of New York. Only one source says March 15, 1885<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> and his obituary states his age to be 69 in December 1954, which would then indicate the birth year as 1885. The draft card of 1942 reveals his birth place to be Dzia\u0142y\u0144, but it is unclear, which of the 4 places of this name in Poland it could have been. \n\nAccording to Fairfield's book, he built his first violin already at age 9 in 1895, which would indicate that he came from a luthier or a musical family. In 1903, by the age of 17, he was a trained violin maker.<ref name=\"Fairfield\"></ref> \n\nAs many Poles of the time would leave the poverty and the Russian and German nationalist oppression of partitioned Poland, he joined his family in the [[United States]]. The year [[1904]], when he would be 17-18 years old, is listed as the year of his immigration in the 1920 New York census, where his name is misspelled William Wikanoski and transcribed as Wikanski. <ref name=\"1920census\">1920 US New York Census, Brooklyn</ref>\n<br>As many Poles would do to assimilate in the United States, it seems he changed his Polish first name to a somewhat similar English name with the same initial, William, which would not be given as a child name in Poland, unless as the German form Wilhelm, known in the German speaking partitions of Poland. One source lists his Polish first name as Wladyslaw.<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> In the New York census records, there are several people listed with the last name Wilkanowski. At least one male relative of Wilkanowski already resided in New York - the father of his cousin Maximilian, born in New York. In [[1905]], William and his wife Amelia had their daughter Helen; several children followed, listed as 7 children, all born in New York and speaking Polish, by the year 1920.<ref name=\"1920census\"></ref>\n\nWilliam worked in the shops of Ditson (Boston) and Fred [[Gretsch]] ([[New York City]]) until he opened his own workshop and store in Brooklyn, New York. He was also a violinist himself and was a member of a polka band in the 1920s.<ref name=\"Cozio Archive\"></ref>\n\n==Career in the United States==\nHe was listed as a violin maker in [[Brooklyn]] by 1933, and at least one violin made in Brooklyn dates to 1924. From 1937 to 1941, he worked in both an era and a location renowned for the [[jazz guitar]]. Gretsch offered Wilkanowski's violins in a 1940 flyer with the text \"his own personal work\u2026no other hand touches them.\" His violins were offered from $50\u2013150.\n\nWilkanowski is thought to have produced 5,000 violins and 100 [[viola]]s by 1942. <ref name=\"Fairfield\"></ref> Some of the higher quality violins were marked with an inlayed logo of the stylized letter ''W''; these instruments are thought to be entirely of his own making, while many of the others were made in the shops with assistants. The Gretsch Company released the Synchromatic line during the early '40s also, which were also [[archtop guitar]]s, but shared no other similarities with Wilkanowski guitars. His role in the Synchromatic is not known.\n\nAlthough known for his violins, Wilkanowski also produced a limited number of archtop guitars.  By 1942 he had sold 30 of these instruments, each unique in appointments and features, at $400 each, except for two deluxe Airway guitars, sold for $600. This price was in line with what was being charged for a D\u2019Angelico New Yorker, or a [[Gibson Guitar Corporation]] Super 400. There is no evidence of guitars made by Wilkanowski after 1943, instead he continued making and successfully selling violins until 1952.\n\n== Features of his guitars ==\nMost of the Wilkanowski guitars would look not like regular jazz guitars, but very much like oversized and slightly squished violins or small cellos with an added guitar neck. Some of his guitars did not have the cello shape, but rather a more conventional archtop shape, without the cello-like points above the waist. The Wilkanowski headstock is thought to have been the main influence in the headstock for the current [[Ovation Guitar]]. Many of his guitars have the unique flattened oval Wilkanowski headstock, although some featured a violin like scroll of aluminium, and some of his headstocks would just be like conventional guitar headstock. The backs of most of his guitars were one piece of flamed [[maple]], with no center joint. The wood William used would often be the Po Valley Poplar, a figured cello tonewood that can resemble maple. The finishing techniques included very light stain, or a violin color finish, and light sealer. The multiple layer binding was wooden, something fairly innovative at the time, and was raised above the level of the top and back plates. The f holes varied by instrument, standard shape, segmented, and later more modern cutouts appeared.  Some of the Instruments displayed the name AIRWAY, some had a W on the headstock, and some remained unbranded. Some of the guitars carry serial numbers, a signature, or a label. Several of the guitars are labeled Wilkanowski and Son, although nothing is known of the son's responsibility. One of these guitars, the Airway W-4 model with abalone shell inlayed rim around the entire body front and abalone ornaments on the neck, was given as a gift to Johnny Cash by his wife June in the 1980s. Johnny kept this guitar until his death, and the instrument was subsequently sold at the [[Johnny Cash]] estate auction by [[Sotheby's]] in 2004, to appear again on auction in 2009.<ref name=\"Cash\"></ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWilliam married a fellow Pole, Michalina Amelia Glowinska<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> in New York and together they have raised 7 daughters: Genevieve (1907-1977), Carolyne, Helen, Florence, Irene, Viola and Natalie (1924-2009), and the 2 sons Henry (1922-1965) and Theodore Joseph (1919-1969). His wife would go by her middle name Amelia, sometimes registered as Emilia. In the 1940 New York census, she is listed as Emily and 53 years old, 1 year older than William listed as \"Wm\", 52 years old. Five of their youngest children - the 3 girls and 2 sons - are listed living with the parents in the same 1940 census, which indicates their 4 oldest daughters already moved out and married.<ref name=\"1940census\">1940 US Census, New York, Brooklyn</ref> The name Joseph seems to have been significant to Wilkanowski, who would also label some of his violins with the name \"Juzek\", which is the slightly misspelled Polish diminutive of Joseph. \n\nIn 1942, both of Wilkanowski's sons were drafted for the World War 2 Young Man Draft. In Henry's draft card, there is a detailed description of William as the head (of the house) of the draftee. This 1942 draft card provides the date and place of William's birth, misspelled as the non-existing place \"Dziatyn\" (as the Polish small letter [[\u0142]] looks very much like the Latin [[t]]), his age as 56, his height as 5'4, his weight as 155 pounds, his eye color as brown, hair as gray and complexion as ruddy. In the occupation field, William was not disclosed as luthier, but as self employed.<ref name=\"draft1942\"></ref><br>\nHenry was sent to fight in Germany with his infantry battalion, which earned him a military grave at the Long Island National cemetery,<ref name=\"graveHenry\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/82604147/henry-wilkanowski] Grave of Henry Wilkanowski</ref> and Theodore became a corporal in WWII.<ref name=\"graveTheodore\">\n[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/29543508/theodore-j-wilkanowski] Grave of Theodore J. Wilkanowski</ref>\n\n== Litterature ==\n* Bacon, Tony. (2005) ''The History of the American Guitar''. {{ISBN|1-4027-3028-4}}\n* Hunter, Dave. (2003) ''Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia''. Thunder Bay Press. {{ISBN|1-59223-051-2}}\n* Fairfield, John H. (1942) ''Known Violin Makers''. Virtuoso Pubns Inc. {{ISBN|0-918624-00-2}}\n\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Guitar makers]]\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:American musical instrument makers]]\n", "text_old": "(Wladyslaw)<ref name=\"heritage\">[https://www.myheritage.es/names/natalie_wilkanowski] Parents of Natalie Wilkanowski</ref> '''William \"Willi\" Wilkanowski''' (born November 15, [[1886]]<ref name=\"grave\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/171555966/william-wilkanowski] Grave of William Wilkanowski Grave with DOB and date of interring</ref> in [[Dzia\u0142y\u0144]],<ref name=\"draft1942\">U.S. World War II Draft Registration Cards, 1942</ref> [[Poland]], dead December 8, [[1954]] in Long Island, USA)<ref name=\"obituary\">[https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/52894684/?terms=wilkanowski] William Wilkanowski Obituary, The Brooklyn Daily Eagle, December 11, 1954</ref> was a [[Polish-American]] [[violin]]-maker, [[guitar]]-maker and violinist. He was a very productive [[luthier]], known for making over 5000 violins and 100 violas with his staff at his workshop.<ref name=\"Fairfield\">Fairfield, John H. (1942) ''Known Violin Makers''. Virtuoso Pubns Inc. {{ISBN|0-918624-00-2}}</ref> He also created 30 unique, high-end archtop guitars, one of which, the Wilkanowski Airway W-4, was famously owned by [[Johnny Cash]] since the 1980s.<ref name=\"Cash\">[https://www.retrofret.com/product.asp?ProductID=4172] Wilkanowski Airway W-4 owned by Cash, listed as auction item</ref>\n\nWilkanowski was also known to be a family man, marrying early to his wife Amelia (1885/1886 - May 10, 1952),<ref name=\"graveWife\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/171555967/amelia-wilkanowski] Grave of Amelia Wilkanowski</ref> with whom he had raised 9 children. When Amelia got sick, in 1950 he sold his shop property and moved his workshop to their Long Island home to be close to her and look after her. After she died of the illness in 1952, he became very depressed and despondent without her.<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref> He stopped making instruments altogether and lost his source of income, which negatively affected his finances, adding to his depressive state.<ref name=\"Cozio Archive\">William Wilkanowski biography article by Ira Kraemer in the Cozio Archive</ref> In early December 1954, he finally committed suicide<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref> and was laid to rest next to Amelia on December 13, 1954.<ref name=\"obituary\"></ref><ref name=\"grave\"></ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWilkanowski was born on November 15, 1886 as listed on his grave and in the draft card, and the year 1886 indicated as estimated in several census records of New York. Only one source says March 15, 1885<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> and his obituary states his age to be 69 in December 1954, which would then indicate the birth year as 1885. The draft card of 1942 reveals his birth place to be Dzia\u0142y\u0144, but it is unclear, which of the 4 places of this name in Poland it could have been. \n<br>\nAccording to Fairfield's book, he built his first violin already at age 9 in 1895, which would indicate that he came from a luthier or a musical family. In 1903, by the age of 17, he was a trained violin maker.<ref name=\"Fairfield\"></ref> \n<br>\nAs many Poles of the time would leave the poverty and the Russian and German nationalist oppression of partitioned Poland, he joined his family in the [[United States]]. The year [[1904]], when he would be 17-18 years old, is listed as the year of his immigration in the 1920 New York census, where his name is misspelled William Wikanoski and transcribed as Wikanski. <ref name=\"1920census\">1920 New York Census, Brooklyn</ref>\n<br|As many Poles would do to assimilate in the United States, it seems he changed his Polish first name to a somewhat similar English name with the same initial letter, William, which would not be given as a child name in Poland, unless as the German form Wilhelm, known in the German speaking partitions of Poland. One source lists his Polish first name as Wladyslaw.<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> In the New York census records, there are several people listed with the last name Wilkanowski. At least one male relative of Wilkanowski already resided in New York - the father of his cousin Maximilian, born in New York. In [[1905]], William and his wife Amelia had their daughter Helen; several children followed, listed as 7 children, all born in New York and speaking Polish, by the year 1920.<ref name=\"1920census\"></ref>\n<br> \nWilliam worked in the shops of Ditson (Boston) and Fred [[Gretsch]] ([[New York City]]) until he opened his own workshop and store in Brooklyn, New York. He was also a violinist himself and was a member of a polka band in the 1920s.<ref name=\"Cozio Archive\"></ref>\n\n==Career in the United States==\nHe was listed as a violin maker in [[Brooklyn]] by 1933, and at least one violin made in Brooklyn dates to 1924. From 1937 to 1941, he worked in both an era and a location renowned for the [[jazz guitar]]. Gretsch offered Wilkanowski's violins in a 1940 flyer with the text \"his own personal work\u2026no other hand touches them.\" His violins were offered from $50\u2013150.\n\nWilkanowski is thought to have produced 5,000 violins and 100 [[viola]]s by 1942. <ref name=\"Fairfield\"></ref> Some of the higher quality violins were marked with an inlayed logo of the stylized letter ''W''; these instruments are thought to be entirely of his own making, while many of the others were made in the shops with assistants. The Gretsch Company released the Synchromatic line during the early '40s also, which were also [[archtop guitar]]s, but shared no other similarities with Wilkanowski guitars. His role in the Synchromatic is not known.\n\nAlthough known for his violins, Wilkanowski also produced a limited number of archtop guitars.  By 1942 he had sold 30 of these instruments, each unique in appointments and features, at $400 each, except for two deluxe Airway guitars, sold for $600. This price was in line with what was being charged for a D\u2019Angelico New Yorker, or a [[Gibson Guitar Corporation]] Super 400. There is no evidence of guitars made by Wilkanowski after 1943, instead he continued making and successfully selling violins until 1952.\n\n== Features of his guitars ==\nMost of the Wilkanowski guitars would look not like regular jazz guitars, but very much like oversized and slightly squished violins or small cellos with an added guitar neck. Some of his guitars did not have the cello shape, but rather a more conventional archtop shape, without the cello-like points above the waist. The Wilkanowski headstock is thought to have been the main influence in the headstock for the current [[Ovation Guitar]]. Many of his guitars have the unique flattened oval Wilkanowski headstock, although some featured a violin like scroll of aluminium, and some of his headstocks would just be like conventional guitar headstock. The backs of most of his guitars were one piece of flamed [[maple]], with no center joint. The wood William used would often be the Po Valley Poplar, a figured cello tonewood that can resemble maple. The finishing techniques included very light stain, or a violin color finish, and light sealer. The multiple layer binding was wooden, something fairly innovative at the time, and was raised above the level of the top and back plates. The f holes varied by instrument, standard shape, segmented, and later more modern cutouts appeared.  Some of the Instruments displayed the name AIRWAY, some had a W on the headstock, and some remained unbranded. Some of the guitars carry serial numbers, a signature, or a label. Several of the guitars are labeled Wilkanowski and Son, although nothing is known of the son's responsibility. One of these guitars, the Airway W-4 model with abalone shell inlayed rim around the entire body front and abalone ornaments on the neck, was given as a gift to Johnny Cash by his wife June in the 1980s. Johnny kept this guitar until his death, and the instrument was subsequently sold at the [[Johnny Cash]] estate auction by [[Sotheby's]] in 2004, to appear again on auction in 2009.<ref name=\"Cash\"></ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWilliam married a fellow Pole, Michalina Amelia Glowinska<ref name=\"heritage\"></ref> in New York and together they have raised 7 daughters: Genevieve (1907-1977), Carolyne, Helen, Florence, Irene, Viola and Natalie (1924-2009), and the 2 sons Henry (1922-1965) and Theodore Joseph (1919-1969). His wife would go by her middle name Amelia, sometimes registered as Emilia. In the 1940 New York census, she is listed as Emily and 53 years old, 1 year older than William listed as \"Wm\", 52 years old. Five of their youngest children - the 3 girls and 2 sons - are listed living with the parents in the same 1940 census, which indicates their 4 oldest daughters already moved out and married.<ref name=\"1940census\">1940 US Census, New York, Brooklyn</ref> The name Joseph seems to have been significant to Wilkanowski, who would also label some of his violins with the name \"Juzek\", which is the slightly misspelled Polish diminutive of Joseph. \n\nIn 1942, both of Wilkanowski's sons were drafted for the World War 2 Young Man Draft. In Henry's draft card, there is a detailed description of William as the head (of the house) of the draftee. This 1942 draft card provides the date and place of William's birth, misspelled as the non-existing place \"Dziatyn\" (as the Polish small letter [[\u0142]] looks very much like the Latin [[t]]), his age as 56, his height as 5'4, his weight as 155 pounds, his eye color as brown, hair as gray and complexion as ruddy. In the occupation field, William was not disclosed as luthier, but as self employed.<ref name=\"draft1942\"></ref><br>\nHenry was sent to fight in Germany with his infantry battalion, which earned him a military grave at the Long Island National cemetery,<ref name=\"graveHenry\">[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/82604147/henry-wilkanowski] Grave of Henry Wilkanowski</ref> and Theodore became a corporal in WWII.<ref name=\"graveTheodore\">\n[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/29543508/theodore-j-wilkanowski] Grave of Theodore J. Wilkanowski</ref>\n\n== Litterature ==\n* Bacon, Tony. (2005) ''The History of the American Guitar''. {{ISBN|1-4027-3028-4}}\n* Hunter, Dave. (2003) ''Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia''. Thunder Bay Press. {{ISBN|1-59223-051-2}}\n* Fairfield, John H. (1942) ''Known Violin Makers''. Virtuoso Pubns Inc. {{ISBN|0-918624-00-2}}\n\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Guitar makers]]\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:American musical instrument makers]]\n", "name_user": "Wieszczy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:formatting,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilkanowski"}
{"title_page": "Oncosiphon pilulifer", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant native to Africa}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image=Onchosiphon piluliferum - Flickr - Kevin Thiele.jpg\n|genus=Oncosiphon\n|species=pilulifer\n|authority=(L.f.) K\u00e4llersj\u00f6\n|synonyms_ref={{r|powo}}\n|synonyms={{Species list\n|Cenocline globifera| K.Koch\n|Chrysanthemum obtusum| Kuntze\n|Cotula globifera| Thunb.\n|Cotula pilulifera| L.f.\n|Matricaria globifera| Fenzl ex Harv.\n|Matricaria pilulifera| Druce\n|Pentzia globifera| Hutch.\n|Pentzia pilulifera| (L.f.) Fourc.\n|Tanacetum globiferum| DC.\n|Tanacetum obtusum| Thunb.\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Oncosiphon pilulifer''''' (often spelled ''piluliferum'') is a [[flowering plant]] in the [[Asteraceae|daisy family]] (Asteraceae) native to South Africa and Lesotho.{{r|powo}} It is known as '''globe chamomile''' and sometimes '''stinknet''' due to its strong, unpleasant odor. It is a species of \"least concern\" (low conservation concern) in South Africa{{r|sanbi}} and considered [[invasive species|invasive]] in some parts of North America.{{r|duharnel2019}}\n\n==As an introduced species==\nGlobe chamomile is considered invasive in [[California]] and [[Arizona]]. First seen in the United States in [[Los Angeles]] and [[San Diego]] in the early 1980s, it heavily infests the counties between those cities.{{r|sdcw}} It is expanded its range to the [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] area in the first decade of the 2000s{{r|azc1|duharnel2019}} and can be found in [[Maricopa County|Maricopa]], [[Pinal County|Pinal]], and [[Pima County|Pima]] counties.{{r|sdcw}}  Rapid spread in Maricopa County occurred due to above-average fall and winter precipitation in 2016, and 2018\u20132020. Heavy infestations occurred in northern parts of [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]] as well as to the south along the [[I-10 in Arizona|I-10]] corridor towards [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]].  The first recorded growth in [[Tucson]] was in 2015.{{r|sdcw}}\n\nIt is also found in the Australian states of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and [[Western Australia]].{{r|hgau}}\n\nIn North America, globe chamomile grows from seed in November to January when it begins flowering and setting new seeds. With sufficient moisture, three generations can grow by April. Wind-born seed transportation spreads the plant which takes root in sunny, disturbed soil in natural and cultivated areas. Plants can reach {{cvt|2|feet}} in height and can cause skin irritation or allergic reaction through contact with the plant or inhalation of its pollen.{{r|duharnel2019}}\n\nA single plant can contain up to 4000 flower balls, each ball being made up of hundreds of flowers{{r|azc1}}\n\nThe plant can be removed physically or killed with [[triclopyr]]; it is resistant to [[glyphosate-based herbicide]]s.{{r|aznps}}\n\n==Invasiveness==\nThe Arizona department of Agriculture considers it a \"high priority pest for quarantine, control or mitigation if a significant threat to a crop, commodity, or habitat is known to exist.\"{{r|azc1}} Other problems are its density which displaces native vegetation, high flammability of dried out patches, and caustic smoke when burned.{{r|sdcw}}\n\n==Other names==\n\nSynonyms include ''matricaria globifera'' because it was previously in the ''[[matricaria]]'' genus, and ''pentzia globifera'', named for 18th century Swedish botanist [[Carolus Johannes Pentz]].{{r|hgau}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200px>\nFile:Oncosiphon_pilulifer.jpg|Invasive growth in Arizona\nFile:Oncosiphon pilulifer 2.jpg|Plant in bloom\nFile:Oncosiphon pilulifer 3.jpg|Growing along street in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=aznps>{{cite web |title=GlobechamomileOncosiphonPiluliferum |url=https://aznps.com/wp-content/uploads/Globe-Chamomille-Final.pdf |website=aznps.com |publisher=Arizona Native Plant Society |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=duharnel2019>{{cite news |last1=DuHarnel |first1=Jonathan |title=Globe Chamomile, an invasive species in Arizona |url=https://arizonadailyindependent.com/2019/04/27/globe-chamomile-an-invasive-species-in-arizona/ |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=Arizona Independent News Network |date=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=powo>{{cite web |title=''Oncosiphon pilulifer'' (L.f.) K\u00e4llersj\u00f6 |url=http://plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:945195-1 |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=[[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=sanbi>Foden, W. & Potter, L. 2005. Oncosiphon piluliferum (L.f.) K\u00e4llersj\u00f6. National Assessment: Red List of South African Plants version 2017.1. Accessed on 2020/04/04</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"azc1\">{{cite news |last1=Woods |first1=Alden |title=Instagram-friendly flowers are taking over the Phoenix area. One problem: They're invasive weeds |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-environment/2019/04/10/what-is-globe-chamomile-and-why-is-it-considered-an-invasive-species-in-arizona/3420062002/ |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=[[Arizona Republic]] |date=Apr 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hgau\">{{cite web |title=Globe Chamomile |url=http://www.herbiguide.com.au/Descriptions/hg_Globe_Chamomile.htm |website=herbguide.com.au |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sdcw\">{{cite web |title=Stinknet (also called Globe Chamomile) - (Oncosiphon piluliferum) |url=http://www.sdcwma.org/species/stinknet.php |website=sdcwma.org |publisher=Sonoran Desert Cooperative Weed Management Area |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n}}\n{{Taxonbar|from1=Q43374849|from2=Q15572256}}\n\n[[Category:Anthemideae]]\n[[Category:Flora of Africa]]\n[[Category:Invasive species in Australia]]\n[[Category:Invasive species in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant native to Africa}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image=Onchosiphon piluliferum - Flickr - Kevin Thiele.jpg\n|genus=Oncosiphon\n|species=pilulifer\n|authority=(L.f.) K\u00e4llersj\u00f6\n|synonyms_ref={{r|powo}}\n|synonyms={{Species list\n|Cenocline globifera| K.Koch\n|Chrysanthemum obtusum| Kuntze\n|Cotula globifera| Thunb.\n|Cotula pilulifera| L.f.\n|Matricaria globifera| Fenzl ex Harv.\n|Matricaria pilulifera| Druce\n|Pentzia globifera| Hutch.\n|Pentzia pilulifera| (L.f.) Fourc.\n|Tanacetum globiferum| DC.\n|Tanacetum obtusum| Thunb.\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Oncosiphon pilulifer''''' (often spelled ''piluliferum'') is a [[flowering plant]] in the [[Asteraceae|daisy family]] (Asteraceae) native to South Africa and Lesotho.{{r|powo}} It is known as '''globe chamomile''' and sometimes '''stinknet''' due to its strong, unpleasant odor. It is a species of \"least concern\" (low conservation concern) in South Africa{{r|sanbi}} and considered [[invasive species|invasive]] in some parts of North America.{{r|duharnel2019}}\n\n==As an introduced species==\nGlobe chamomile is considered invasive in [[California]] and [[Arizona]]. First seen in the United States in [[Los Angeles]] and [[San Diego]] in the early 1980s, it heavily infests the counties between those cities.{{r|sdcw}} It is expanded its range to the [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] area in the first decade of the 2000s{{r|azc1|duharnel2019}} and can be found in [[Maricopa County|Maricopa]], [[Pinal County|Pinal]], and [[Pima County|Pima]] counties.{{r|sdcw}}  Rapid spread in Maricopa County occurred due to above-average fall and winter precipitation in 2016, and 2018\u20132020. Heavy infestations occurred in northern parts of [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]] as well as to the south along the [[I-10 in Arizona|I-10]] corridor towards [[Casa Grande, Arizona|Casa Grande]]  The first recorded growth in [[Tucson]] was in 2015.{{r|sdcw}}\n\nIt is also found in the Australian states of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and [[Western Australia]].{{r|hgau}}\n\nIn North America, globe chamomile grows from seed in November to January when it begins flowering and setting new seeds. With sufficient moisture, three generations can grow by April. Wind-born seed transportation spreads the plant which takes root in sunny, disturbed soil in natural and cultivated areas. Plants can reach {{cvt|2|feet}} in height and can cause skin irritation or allergic reaction through contact with the plant or inhalation of its pollen.{{r|duharnel2019}}\n\nA single plant can contain up to 4000 flower balls, each ball being made up of hundreds of flowers{{r|azc1}}\n\nThe plant can be removed physically or killed with [[triclopyr]]; it is resistant to [[glyphosate-based herbicide]]s.{{r|aznps}}\n\n==Invasiveness==\nThe Arizona department of Agriculture considers it a \"high priority pest for quarantine, control or mitigation if a significant threat to a crop, commodity, or habitat is known to exist.\"{{r|azc1}} Other problems are its density which displaces native vegetation, high flammability of dried out patches, and caustic smoke when burned.{{r|sdcw}}\n\n==Other names==\n\nSynonyms include ''matricaria globifera'' because it was previously in the ''[[matricaria]]'' genus, and ''pentzia globifera'', named for 18th century Swedish botanist [[Carolus Johannes Pentz]].{{r|hgau}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200px>\nFile:Oncosiphon_pilulifer.jpg|Invasive growth in Arizona\nFile:Oncosiphon pilulifer 2.jpg|Plant in bloom\nFile:Oncosiphon pilulifer 3.jpg|Growing along street in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=aznps>{{cite web |title=GlobechamomileOncosiphonPiluliferum |url=https://aznps.com/wp-content/uploads/Globe-Chamomille-Final.pdf |website=aznps.com |publisher=Arizona Native Plant Society |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=duharnel2019>{{cite news |last1=DuHarnel |first1=Jonathan |title=Globe Chamomile, an invasive species in Arizona |url=https://arizonadailyindependent.com/2019/04/27/globe-chamomile-an-invasive-species-in-arizo