eover,\u201d Vol. 26, N\u00b0 13, June 24, 1981, pps.&nbsp;119\u2013128 {{OCLC|4928661667|4661381272}}\n* \u201cDigitization Is On The Way For [[Fast Fourier transform|FFT]] Designs,\u201d Vol. 26, N\u00b0 15, August 5, 1981, pps.&nbsp;99\u2013106 {{OCLC|4928662915}}\n* \u201cAdd the [[Fast Fourier transform|FFT]] to Your Box of Design Tools,\u201d Vol. 26, N\u00b0 18, September 16, 1981, pps.&nbsp;83\u201388\n* \u201cAs [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chips Mature, Support Chips Proliferate,\u201d Vol. 27, N\u00b0 1, January 6, 1982, pps.&nbsp;155\u2013202 {{OCLC|4928674427}}\n* \u201cNew-Generation [[Video Display Controller|CRT-Controller]] ICs Cut Display Costs, Increase Capabilities,\u201d Vol. 27, N\u00b0 10, May 12, 1982, pps.&nbsp;39\u201346 {{OCLC|4433265520}}\n* \u201c[[Digital signal processing|Digital Signal-Processing]] [[Integrated circuit|ICs]]{{space|1}}...{{space|1}},\u201d Vol. 27, N\u00b0 14, July 16, 1982\n* \u201c[http://www.edn.com/electronics-products/other/4318986/EDN-Product-Showcase-ICs-and-semiconductors EDN Product Showcase: ICs and Semiconductors,\u201d] Vol. 27, N\u00b0 14, July 16, 1982\n* \u201c[[Memory bandwidth|Byte-Wide-Memory]] Standard Gains Adherents as Designers Discover Its Advantages,\u201d Vol. 27, N\u00b0 15, August 4, 1982, pps.&nbsp;53\u201358\n* \u201c[[CMOS]] Microprocessor and Microcomputer [[Integrated circuit|ICs]],\u201d Vol. 27, N\u00b0 19, September 29, 1982, pps.&nbsp;88\u2013100\n* \u201c[[Transistor\u2013transistor logic|TTL]] Enhancements and Extensions,\u201d November 24, 1982, pps.&nbsp;95\u2013102\n* \u201cHands-On Investigations Help Exploit [[CMOS]] Designs,\u201d Vol. 28, N\u00b0 8, April 14, 1983, pg. 13 (7-1/2 pages) {{OCLC|4926374764|4660827672}}\n* \u201c[[Digital Signal Processing]] Advances Slowly, But Steadily,\u201d Vol. 28, N\u00b0 14, July 7, 1983, pg. 60\u201372\n* \u201cHands-On Network-Design Project Gives Insight Into LAN Features,\u201d Vol. 29, N\u00b0 6, March 22, 1984, pps.&nbsp;219\u2013232 {{OCLC|4928688895|4661412845}}\n* \u201c[[Very Large Scale Integration|VLSI-Based]] [[Local area network|LAN]]-Controller Chip Eases [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]-to-Network Interface,\u201d Vol. 29, N\u00b0 9, May 4, 1984, pps.&nbsp;207\u2013220 {{OCLC|4928666410|4661411667}}\n* \u201cEnhanced [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]s Bring New Life to Old Devices,\u201d January 1985, pps.&nbsp;124\u2013138\n* \u201cMicroprocessor Support Chips Present a Wide Array of Choices,\u201d Vol. 30, N\u00b0 25, March 7, 1985\n* \u201cThird Generation [[Digital signal processor|DSPs]] Put Advance Functions on Chip,\u201d Vol. 30, N\u00b0 16, July 11, 1985, pps.&nbsp;59\u201368\n* \u201cKeep [[Breadboard]] Simple in Hands-On [[Digital signal processor|DSP]] Projects,\u201d September 5, 1985, pg. 225 (10 pages)\n* \u201cSupport Chips Mature to Upstage the Host Microprocessor,\u201d Vol. 31, N\u00b0 6, March 20, 1986, pps.&nbsp;116\u2013167 {{OCLC|4928696817|4661423162}}\n* \u201c[[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]-Like [[Digital signal processing|DSP]] Chips,\u201d Vol. 32, N\u00b0 18, September 3, 1987, pps.&nbsp;155\u2013186 {{OCLC|4928712225}}\n* \u201cNew Software Tools Run IBM PC Software on a Variety of 32-Bit [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]s,\u201d February 18, 1988, pps.&nbsp;93, 95\u201397, 100\n{{ref end}}\n<!--------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n<hr style=\"color:#A9A9A9;width:20em\" />\n{{ref begin|100em}}\n; ''EDN's'' Annual Chip Directories\n{{ref end}}\n{{ref begin|50em}}\n* ''Fourth Annual Microprocessor Directory,'' Vol. 22, N\u00b0 21, November 20, 1977, pps.&nbsp;44\u201383\n* ''EDN's Seventh Annual [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chip Directory,'' Vol. 26, N\u00b0 20, November 5, 1980\n* ''EDN's Eighth Annual [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chip Directory,'' November 11, 1981, pg. 100\n* ''EDN's Tenth Annual [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chip Directory,'' Vol. 28, N\u00b0 22, November 10, 1983, pps.&nbsp;111\u2013256\n* ''EDN's Eleventh Annual [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chip Directory,'' Vol. 29, N\u00b0 23, November 15, 1984\n* ''EDN's 14th Annual [[Microprocessor|\u03bcP]]/[[Microcontroller|\u03bcC]] Chip Directory,'' Vol. 32, N\u00b0 24, November 26, 1987, pps.&nbsp;100\u2013187 {{OCLC|4928712791}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n== Professional affiliations and hobbies ==\n* Member, [[International Society of Automation]], since the late 1950s\n* Cushman filed several patents and copyrights\n\n; Selected stage plays & screenplays\n* ''Judson Mansions'' or ''The Barbarians,'' A melodrama in three acts, 30 March 1950<ref name=\"Copyright Catalog 1950\" />\n* ''The Scientific Approach to Getting Married in a Hurry,'' a filmplay by Robert Herman Cushman, 7 November 1963<ref name=\"Copyright Catalog 1963\" />\n\n== Ancestry and family ==\n; Notable ancestry\nCushman, by way of his father, Clifford Howell Cushman (1891\u20131974), was a tenth-generation [[lineal descendant]] of [[Thomas Cushman (Plymouth colonist)|Thomas Cushman]] (1608\u20131691) and wife, [[Mary Allerton]] (1616\u20131699) \u2014 settlers of the [[Plymouth Colony]].  The lineage is all paternal, hence the same surname.<ref name=\"Thomas & Mary Cushman lineage\" group=lower-alpha /> [[Mary Allerton]] was a [[List of Mayflower passengers|passenger]] on the [[Mayflower]], the first ship to arrive in [[Plymouth Colony|Plymouth]] in 1620.  [[Thomas Cushman (Plymouth colonist)|Thomas Cushman]] was a passenger on the [[Fortune (Plymouth Colony ship)|Fortune]], the second ship to arrive in 1621.  Cushman was also an eleventh generation [[lineal descendant]] of [[Francis Eaton (Mayflower passenger)|Francis Eaton]], also a [[List of Mayflower passengers|passenger]] on the [[Mayflower]] and settler of [[Plymouth Colony|Plymouth]]<ref name=\"Francis Eaton\" group=lower-alpha /> \u2014 a fourth generation female descendant of [[Francis Eaton (Mayflower passenger)|Francis Eaton]] married a third generation descendant of [[Robert Cushman|Robert]] and [[Mary Allerton|Mary Cushman]].\n\nNowadays, tens of millions of Americans have at least one ancestor from the [[Plymouth Colony]], many of whom affiliated with the [[Mayflower Society]].  But, according to [[Galton\u2013Watson process|Galton-Watson]] probability, only a fraction of that number have an unbroken chain of [[Patrilineality|paternal]] lineage maintaining the same surname.\n\n; Family\nCushman married Rose Katherine Clausing October 4, 1952, in [[Butler County, Ohio]].  They had a daughter and a son and remained married {{Cardinal to word|{{age|1952|10|04|1996|01|27}}}} years, until his death.<ref name=\"NYT Obit\" />\n\n== Notes and references ==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha|100em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Thomas & Mary Cushman lineage\">[[Thomas Cushman (Plymouth colonist)|Thomas Cushman]] & [[Mary Allerton]] (1st), Thomas Cushman (2nd: 1637\u20131726), Benjamin Cushman (3rd: 1691\u20131770), Caleb Cushman (4th: 1715\u20131778), Gideon Cushman (5th: 1750\u20131845), Caleb Cushman (6th: 1779\u20131859), Alexander Cushman (7th: 1812\u20131880), Herman Alexander Cushman (8th: 1863\u20131933), Clifford Howell Cushman (9th: 1891\u20131974), Robert Herman Cushman (10th: 1924\u20131996)<br /><br /></ref>\n<ref name=\"Francis Eaton\">[[Francis Eaton (Mayflower passenger)|Francis Eaton]] & Christian Penn (1st), Benjamin Eaton, Sr. (2nd: 1627\u20131712), Benjamin Eaton, Jr. (3rd: 1664\u20131739), Sarah Eaton (4th: 1695\u20131737, married to Benjamin Cushman; 1691\u20131770), Caleb Cushman (5th: 1715\u20131778), Gideon Cushman (6th: 1750\u20131845), Caleb Cushman (7th: 1779\u20131859), Alexander Cushman (8th: 1812\u20131880), Herman Alexander Cushman (9th: 1863\u20131933), Clifford Howell Cushman (10th: 1891\u20131974), Robert Herman Cushman (11th: 1924\u20131996)<br /><br /></ref>\n\n}}\n<!--------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n===References===\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Wilton\">[http://fultonhistory.com/Process%20Small/Newspapers/Newspapers%20%20Out%20of%20NY/Wilton%20CT.%20Bulletin/Wilton%20CT%20%20Bulletin%201996%20Grayscale/Wilton%20CT%20%20Bulletin%201996%20Grayscale%20-%200126.pdf \"Robert Cushman, Resident's Father,\" ''Wilton Bulletin'' (Connecticut), January 31, 1996, pg. 2A]</ref>\n<ref name=\"Electronics Who's Who\">''Who's Who in Electronics,'' 1961 {{OCLC|2428096|22589369}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Pro Children's School Alumni Records\">[http://pcs2.cust5.dcsny.com/user.cfm Professional Children's School Online Alumni Records (retrieved 20 February 2013)]</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">\"Cushman, Robert H.\" (obituary), ''[[New York Times]],'' January 30, 1996</ref>\n<ref name=\"ISA Journal\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=rmI2AQAAIAAJ&q=cushman#search_anchor \"Datastrom PR,\"] ''[[International Society of Automation|ISA Journal]],'' Vol. 6, pg. 79, 1959 {{ISSN|0096-0810}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Electronic Industries\">''Electronic Industries,'' Caldwell-Clements, [[Bristol, Connecticut]] (publisher), Vol. 21, N\u00b0 1, 1962, pg. 25</ref>\n<ref name=\"American Way Playbill\">[http://www.playbillvault.com/Show/Detail/Cast/12012/The-American-Way-at-Center-Theatre ''The American Way],'' ''[[Playbill]]'' Vault, Playbill, Inc. (accessed 20 February 2013)</ref>\n<ref name=\"Copyright Catalog 1950\">[https://archive.org/stream/catalogofcopyrig3434libr/catalogofcopyrig3434libr_djvu.txt ''Catalog of Copyright Entries, Third Series, Vol. 4, Parts 3 & 4, Number 1, Dramas and Works Prepared for Oral Delivery,'' January\u2013June 1950]</ref>\n<ref name=\"Copyright Catalog 1963\">[https://archive.org/stream/catalogofcopyrig31734libr/catalogofcopyrig31734libr_djvu.txt ''Catalog of Copyright Entries, Third Series, Vol. 17, Parts 3 & 4, Number 1, Dramas and Works Prepared for Oral Delivery;'' January\u2013June 1963]</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cushman, Robert Herman}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineering journalists]]\n[[Category:American magazine writers]]\n[[Category:Science journalists]]\n[[Category:Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Old Lyme, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Port Washington, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Engineering journalist||Robert Cushman (disambiguation){{!}}Robert Cushman}}\n{{cleanup-reorganize|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Journalist/doc]]. -->\n| name          = Robert H. Cushman\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = Robert Herman Cushman\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1924|01|26}}\n| birth_place   = Evanston, Illinois\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1996|01|27|1924|01|26}}\n| death_place   = [[Essex, Connecticut]]\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Electrical engineering journalist\n| nationality   = United States\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = United States\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    =  [[Professional Children's School]]<br />[[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notable_works  = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Robert (Bob) Herman Cushman''' (16 January 1924 in [[Evanston, Illinois]] \u2013 27 January 1996 in [[Essex, Connecticut]])<ref name=\"Wilton\" /> was an [[United States|American]] trade magazine journalist who had written extensively across several engineering disciplines, two in particular during the vanguard of rapid technological advances and ensuing market boom of their respective technologies.  In the late 1950s, at the beginning of the [[Space Race]], Cushman had been an editor at ''[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]].''<ref name=\"Electronics Who's Who\" />  From 1962 to the late-1980s, he was an editor for ''[[EDN (magazine)|Electronic Design News]].''  He started out at [[EDN (magazine)|EDN]] as the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] editor and soon rose to Special Features Editor covering [[microprocessor|microprocessing]].  Cushman was widely known within the microprocessing industry for his influential writings in ''[[EDN (magazine)|Electronic Design News]]'' about microprocessors during its infancy in the early 1970s, through its period of rapid growth and development in the 1980s.  His articles, collectively, chronicle the birth and early milestones of microprocessors and, at the time, helped bridge technical development with applications.  Citations of his work are prevalent in documents produced by academicians, engineers, the military, and [[NASA]].\n\nAt the time of Cushman's death, he and his wife were residents of [[Old Lyme, Connecticut]]. Before retiring, he and his wife had been a long-time residents of [[Port Washington, New York]].\n\n== Early career ==\nCushman earned a high school diploma in 1942 from the [[Professional Children's School]] in [[Manhattan, New York|Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Pro Children's School Alumni Records\" /> After the start of [[World War II]], he entered the [[U.S. Navy]] as a [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|Lt. J.G.]].  Upon earning a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], he served in China. After the war, Cushman, an avid sailor, spent two years as a yacht designer with [[Philip Rhodes|Philip L. Rhodes]],<ref name=\"NYT Obit\" /> who later designed the [[Weatherly (yacht)|Weatherly]].  In 1959, after serving as Associate Editor of ''Automatic Control'', Cushman accepted a position as Public Relations Director of Daystrom, Inc., [[San Diego]],<ref name=\"ISA Journal\" /> which was acquired by [[Schlumberger]] in 1962, but continued to operate as a wholly owned subsidiary.<ref name=\"Electronic Industries\" />  Cushman had retired as Senior Editor at [[Cahners Publishing]],<ref name=\"Wilton\" /> a longtime division of [[Reed Elsevier]] and, at the time, parent of ''[[EDN (magazine)|EDN]].''\n\n== Growing up ==\nCushman had been a child actor.  At the age of {{Cardinal to word|{{age|1924|01|16|1939|01|21}}}} \u2014 from January 21, 1939, to June 1, 1939, and from July 17, 1939, to September 23, 1939 \u2014 Cushman had acted in the Broadway play, ''[[George S. Kaufman|The American Way]],'' in the role of Young Alex Hewitt at that [[RKO Roxy Theatre]].  The play ran for 244 performances.<ref name=\"American Way Playbill\" />\n\n== Selected articles ==\n{{ref begin|100em}}\n; ''[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]],'' [[McGraw-Hill]] \u2014 {{ISSN|0005-2175}}\n* \u201cGE Bids for Helicopter Market With [[General Electric T58|T58]],\u201d Vol. 64, N\u00b0 23, June 4, 1956, pg. 60\n* \u201cCornell Instruments For Shock Tubes,\u201d Vol. 65, N\u00b0 18, October 29, 1956, pg. 80\n* \u201c[[Booster (rocketry)|Rocket-Tube]] Ejector Adds To Escape Margin For Jet Pilots,\u201d Vol. 65, N\u00b0 20, November 12, 1956, pps.&nbsp;71\u201377\n* \u201cLewis Pushes Work on Rocket Engines,\u201d Vol. 66, N\u00b0 22, June 3, 1957, pps.&nbsp;10\u201383\n* \u201cAir Problems Attacked in Mid-Manhattan,\u201d Vol. 67, N\u00b0 1, July 8, 1957\n* \u201c[[General Electric CF6|F-103]] Demise Clouds [[Mixed/dual cycle|Dual Cycle]] Future,\u201d Vol. 67, N\u00b0 10, September 9, 1957, pg. 101\n* \u201cGM Seeks 'Fluidity' in $60 Million Engine R&D Facility,\u201d Vol. 67, N\u00b0 14, October 7, 1957 {{OCLC|247469174}}\n* \u201c[[Hypersonic wind tunnel|Hypersonic Tunnels]] Yield Practical Data,\u201d Vol. 67, N\u00b0 16, October 21, 1957\n* \u201cScientist Study [[Mach number|Mach]] 7 [[Ramjet]] Theory,\u201d Vol. 68, N\u00b0 1, January 6, 1958, pps.&nbsp;57\u201359 & 63\n<!-------------------------------------