{"title_page": "Pauropoda", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{Fossil range|40|0}}<small>[[Eocene]] to [[Holocene|Present]]</small>\n| image = Eurypauropodid (12742282145) crop.jpg\n| image_caption = A [[eurypauropod]] from New Zealand\n| taxon = Pauropoda\n| subdivision_ranks = Orders\n| subdivision = \n*[[Hexamerocerata]]\n*[[Tetramerocerata]]\n| synonyms =\n{{taxon list|Heterognathes|de Saussure & Humbert, 1872\n|Heterognatha|T\u00f6m\u00f6sv\u00e1ry, 1883\n|Monopoda| Bollman, 1893}}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"Scheller 2008\">{{cite journal|last1=Scheller|first1=Ulf|title=A reclassification of the Pauropoda (Myriapoda)|journal=International Journal of Myriapodology|date=2008|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1\u201338|doi=10.1163/187525408X316730}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pauropods''' are small, pale, [[millipede]]-like [[arthropod]]s. Around 830 [[species]] in twelve families<ref>{{cite journal |last=Minelli|first=Alessandro |title=Class Chilopoda, Class Symphyla and Class Pauropoda. In: Zhang, Z.-Q. (Ed.) Animal biodiversity: An outline of higher-level classification and survey of taxonomic richness |journal=[[Zootaxa]] |year=2011 |volume=3148 |pages=157\u2013158 |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted_sites/acarology/zhang/pub/Zhang2011Animal-biodiversity.pdf|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3148.1.31 }}</ref> are found worldwide, living in soil and leaf mould. They look rather like [[centipede]]s, but are probably the [[sister group]] to millipedes.<ref name=Gillott2005>{{cite book |author=Cedric Gillott |year=2005 |title=Entomology |edition=3rd |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] |isbn=978-1-4020-3182-3}}</ref> \n\n==Anatomy and ecology==\n[[File:Pauropus amicus.jpg|thumb|left|Ventral and dorsal views of ''[[Pauropus]] amicus'' from New South Wales, Australia.]]\nPauropods are soft, cylindrical animals with bodies {{convert|0.5|to|2|mm|2}} long.<ref name=\"Gillott2005\" /> The first [[instar]] has three pairs of legs, but that number increases with each moult so that adult species may have nine to eleven pairs of legs. They have neither eyes nor hearts, although they do have sensory organs which can detect light. The body segments have ventral tracheal/spiracular pouches forming apodemes similar to those in [[millipede]]s and [[Symphyla]], although the [[Invertebrate trachea|trachea]] usually connected to these structures are absent in most species. There are long sensory hairs located throughout the body segments. Pauropods can usually be identified because of their distinctive anal plate, which is unique to pauropods. Different species of pauropods can be identified based on the size and shape of their anal plate. The [[antenna (biology)|antennae]] are branching, [[biramous]], and segmented, which is distinctive for the group.<ref name=\"Coleman\">{{cite book |author=David C. Coleman, D. A. Crossley, Jr. & Paul F. Hendrix |year=2004 |title=Fundamentals of Soil Ecology |edition=2nd |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |isbn=978-0-12-179726-3 |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pKKDJwu_OlkC&pg=PA133}}</ref> Pauropods are usually either white or brown.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://what-when-how.com/animal-life/subclass-pauropoda/|title=Subclass Pauropoda|website=what-when-how.com|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nPauropods live in the soil, usually at densities of less than 100 per square metre (9/sq&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"Coleman\"/>\n\n==Evolution and systematics==\nThough no fossil pauropods have been found from before the time of the [[Baltic amber]] ({{Ma|40|35}}), they seem to be an old group closely related to the [[millipede]]s (Diplopoda). Their head capsules show great similarities to millipedes: both have three pairs of [[arthropod mouthparts|mouthparts]] and the genital openings occur in the anterior part of the body. Moreover, both groups have a pupoid phase at the end of the embryonic development. The two groups probably have a common origin.\n\nThere are two orders: [[Hexamerocerata]] and [[Tetramerocerata]]; Hexamerocerata has a purely tropical range, while in Tetramerocerata most genera are [[Cosmopolitan distribution|subcosmopolitan]].<ref name=\"Ax\">{{cite book |author=Peter Ax |title=Multicellular Animals: The phylogenetic system of the Metazoa |series=Volume 2 of Multicellular Animals: A New Approach to the Phylogenetic Order in Nature |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] |year=2000 |isbn=978-3-540-67406-1 |chapter=Pauropoda |pages=231\u2013233 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FweHI7uZ198C}}</ref> Hexamerocerata has a 6-segmented and strongly telescopic antennal stalk and a 12-segmented trunk with 12 tergites and 11 pairs of legs. The representatives are white and proportionately long and large. The one family in this order, Millotauropodidae, has one genus and a few species.<ref name=\"Ax\"/> Tetramerocerata has a 4-segmented and scarcely telescopic antennal stalk, 6 tergites, and 8\u201310 pairs of legs. Representatives of this order are often small (sometimes very small), and white or brownish. Most species have nine pairs of legs as adults.<ref name=\"Ax\"/> The four families include [[Pauropodidae]], Afrauropodidae, Brachypauropodidae, and [[Eurypauropodidae]]. Most genera and species belong to the family Pauropodidae.\n\n==Behavior, reproduction, and diet==\nPauropods are shy of light, and will attempt to distance themselves from light sources.<ref name=Myriapoda>{{cite book |last=Minelli |first=Alessandro |year=2011 |title=The Myriapoda - Treatise on Zoology - Anatomy, Taxonomy, Biology. |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |pages=495 |isbn=978-90-04-15611-1}}</ref> Pauropods occasionally migrate upwards or downwards throughout the soil based on moisture levels. Male pauropods place small packets of sperm on the ground, which the females use to impregnate themselves with. Pauropods have been known to eat [[Mold (fungus)|mold]], [[hypha|fungal hyphae]], and the [[root hair]]s of plants.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Ulf Scheller |year=1990 |chapter=Pauropoda |title=Soil Biology Guide |editor=Daniel L. Dindal |location=New York |publisher=[[John Wiley and Sons]] |isbn=978-0-471-04551-9 |pages=861\u2013890}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ulf Scheller |year=2002 |chapter=Pauropoda |title=Biodiversidad, Taxonom\u00eda y Biogeograf\u00eda de Artr\u00f3podos de M\u00e9xico: Hacia una S\u00edntesis su Conocimiento |volume=III |editor1=Jorge Llorente Bousquets |editor2=Juan J. Morrone |location=[[Tlalpan]], Mexico |publisher=[[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional para el Conocimiento y Uso de la Biodiversidad|CONABIO]] |language=Spanish}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Pauropoda}}\n{{commons category|Pauropoda}}\n{{Portal|Arthropods}}\n*[http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/scientific-resources/biodiversity/uk-biodiversity/uk-species/checklists/NHMSYS0000883969/index.html Checklist of British Pauropoda - Natural History Museum]\n*[http://bugs.osu.edu/bugdoc/Shetlar/462/462arthropods/Arthropods23.htm Pauropoda - Ohio State University]\n\n{{Arthropods}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q217512}}\n\n[[Category:Myriapods]]\n[[Category:Arthropod classes]]\n[[Category:Bartonian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Extant Eocene first appearances]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{Fossil range|40|0}}<small>[[Eocene]] to [[Holocene|Present]]</small>\n| image = Eurypauropodid (12742282145) crop.jpg\n| image_caption = A [[eurypauropod]] from New Zealand\n| taxon = Pauropoda\n| subdivision_ranks = Orders\n| subdivision = \n*[[Hexamerocerata]]\n*[[Tetramerocerata]]\n| synonyms =\n{{taxon list|Heterognathes|de Saussure & Humbert, 1872\n|Heterognatha|T\u00f6m\u00f6sv\u00e1ry, 1883\n|Monopoda| Bollman, 1893}}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"Scheller 2008\">{{cite journal|last1=Scheller|first1=Ulf|title=A reclassification of the Pauropoda (Myriapoda)|journal=International Journal of Myriapodology|date=2008|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1\u201338|doi=10.1163/187525408X316730}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pauropods''' are small, pale, [[millipede]]-like [[arthropod]]s. Around 830 [[species]] in twelve families<ref>{{cite journal |last=Minelli|first=Alessandro |title=Class Chilopoda, Class Symphyla and Class Pauropoda. In: Zhang, Z.-Q. (Ed.) Animal biodiversity: An outline of higher-level classification and survey of taxonomic richness |journal=[[Zootaxa]] |year=2011 |volume=3148 |pages=157\u2013158 |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted_sites/acarology/zhang/pub/Zhang2011Animal-biodiversity.pdf|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3148.1.31 }}</ref> are found worldwide, living in soil and leaf mould. They look rather like [[centipede]]s, but are probably the [[sister group]] to millipedes.<ref name=Gillott2005>{{cite book |author=Cedric Gillott |year=2005 |title=Entomology |edition=3rd |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] |isbn=978-1-4020-3182-3}}</ref> \n\n==Anatomy and ecology==\n[[File:Pauropus amicus.jpg|thumb|left|Ventral and dorsal views of ''[[Pauropus]] amicus'' from New South Wales, Australia.]]\nPauropods are soft, cylindrical animals with bodies {{convert|0.5|to|2|mm|2}} long.<ref name=\"Gillott2005\" /> The first [[instar]] has three pairs of legs, but that number increases with each moult so that adult species may have nine to eleven pairs of legs. They have neither eyes nor hearts, although they do have sensory organs which can detect light. The body segments have ventral tracheal/spiracular pouches forming apodemes similar to those in [[millipede]]s and [[Symphyla]], although the [[Invertebrate trachea|trachea]] usually connected to these structures are absent in most species. There are long sensory hairs located throughout the body segments. Pauropods can usually be identified because of their distinctive anal plate, which is unique to pauropods. Different species of pauropods can be identified based on the size and shape of their anal plate. The [[antenna (biology)|antennae]] are branching, [[biramous]], and segmented, which is distinctive for the group.<ref name=\"Coleman\">{{cite book |author=David C. Coleman, D. A. Crossley, Jr. & Paul F. Hendrix |year=2004 |title=Fundamentals of Soil Ecology |edition=2nd |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |isbn=978-0-12-179726-3 |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pKKDJwu_OlkC&pg=PA133}}</ref> Pauropods are usually either white or brown.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://what-when-how.com/animal-life/subclass-pauropoda/|title=Subclass Pauropoda|website=what-when-how.com|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nPauropods live in the soil, usually at densities of less than 100 per square metre (9/sq&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"Coleman\"/>\n\n==Evolution and systematics==\nThough no fossil pauropods have been found from before the time of the [[Baltic amber]] ({{Ma|40|35}}), they seem to be an old group closely related to the [[millipede]]s (Diplopoda). Their head capsules show great similarities to millipedes: both have three pairs of [[arthropod mouthparts|mouthparts]] and the genital openings occur in the anterior part of the body. Moreover, both groups have a pupoid phase at the end of the embryonic development. The two groups probably have a common origin.\n\nThere are two orders: [[Hexamerocerata]] and [[Tetramerocerata]]; Hexamerocerata has a purely tropical range, while in Tetramerocerata most genera are [[Cosmopolitan distribution|subcosmopolitan]].<ref name=\"Ax\">{{cite book |author=Peter Ax |title=Multicellular Animals: The phylogenetic system of the Metazoa |series=Volume 2 of Multicellular Animals: A New Approach to the Phylogenetic Order in Nature |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] |year=2000 |isbn=978-3-540-67406-1 |chapter=Pauropoda |pages=231\u2013233 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FweHI7uZ198C}}</ref> Hexamerocerata has a 6-segmented and strongly telescopic antennal stalk and a 12-segmented trunk with 12 tergites and 11 pairs of legs. The representatives are white and proportionately long and large. The one family in this order, Millotauropodidae, has one genus and a few species.<ref name=\"Ax\"/> Tetramerocerata has a 4-segmented and scarcely telescopic antennal stalk, 6 tergites, and 8\u201310 pairs of legs. Representatives of this order are often small (sometimes very small), and white or brownish. Most species have nine pairs of legs as adults.<ref name=\"Ax\"/> The four families include [[Pauropodidae]], Afrauropodidae, Brachypauropodidae, and [[Eurypauropodidae]]. Most genera and species belong to the family Pauropodidae.\n\n==Behavior, reproduction, and diet==\nPauropods are shy of light, and will attempt to distance themselves from light sources.<ref name=Myriapoda>{{cite book |last=Minelli |first=Alessandro |year=2011 |title=The Myriapoda - Treatise on Zoology - Anatomy, Taxonomy, Biology. |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |pages=495 |isbn=978-90-04-15611-1}}</ref> Pauropods occasionally migrate upwards or downwards throughout the soil based on moisture levels. Male pauropods place small packets of sperm on the ground, which the females use to impregnate themselves with. Pauropods have been known to eat [[mold]], [[hypha|fungal hyphae]], and the [[root hair]]s of plants.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Ulf Scheller |year=1990 |chapter=Pauropoda |title=Soil Biology Guide |editor=Daniel L. Dindal |location=New York |publisher=[[John Wiley and Sons]] |isbn=978-0-471-04551-9 |pages=861\u2013890}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ulf Scheller |year=2002 |chapter=Pauropoda |title=Biodiversidad, Taxonom\u00eda y Biogeograf\u00eda de Artr\u00f3podos de M\u00e9xico: Hacia una S\u00edntesis su Conocimiento |volume=III |editor1=Jorge Llorente Bousquets |editor2=Juan J. Morrone |location=[[Tlalpan]], Mexico |publisher=[[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional para el Conocimiento y Uso de la Biodiversidad|CONABIO]] |language=Spanish}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Pauropoda}}\n{{commons category|Pauropoda}}