{"title_page": "Anzio War Cemetery", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2014}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Distinguish|Beach Head War Cemetery|Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial}}\n\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Anzio War Cemetery\n| image       = Anzio Cimitero Britannico by-RaBoe 031.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| established = \n| country     = [[Italy]]\n| location    = [[Anzio]], [[Lazio]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.456|12.623|display=inline}}\n| type        = \n| style       =\n| owner       = [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n| size        = \n| graves      = 1,056\n| interments  = \n| cremations  = \n| leases      = \n| website     = [http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/2064800/ANZIO%20WAR%20CEMETERY CWGC official website]\n| findagraveid= 2185816\n}}\n__NOTOC__\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Anzio-War-Cemetery.jpg|1000px|thumb|The Anzio War Cemetery.{{ifdc|Image:Anzio-War-Cemetery.jpg|log=2008 June 12}}]] -->\nThe [[Commonwealth of Nations]] '''Anzio War Cemetery''' is to be found about a kilometer from [[Anzio]] town in the [[Lazio]] region of [[Italy]]. It is located {{convert|70|km|abbr=off}} south of [[Rome]]. It should not be confused with the [[Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial]], which is for Americans and is located in [[Nettuno]] at the address \"Piazzale Kennedy, 1\".\n\n==Description and history==\nAnzio War Cemetery is a special and communal cemetery for the local and surrounding peoples. It contains 1,056 graves resulting from [[Operation Shingle]] in 1944 as part of [[World War II]]. Having seen the make up of the [[1st Canadian Division]] which was sent there in 1944 it is clear from the graves that those who rest there were from the units of the 1st Division. There were 1,037 identified casualties.\n\n;Poem\nThere is poem about the Anzio War Cemetery written by Michael Elliott-Binns.<ref name=\"Poem\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.salamanderoasis.org/poems/e/elliott-binns-michael/anziowarcemetery.html |title=Salamander Oasis}}</ref> It is written from the perspective of a man that had experienced a loss in the battle and that was writing for his own personal reasons.<ref name=\"Poem\"/> The author later commented that \"They [the fallen soldiers] seem to be buried on the doorstep of their home.\"<ref name=\"Poem\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.remembrancedaysong.com/ Image references]\n{{Portal bar|Architecture|Italy|World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Burials in Lazio]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in Italy]]\n[[Category:World War II operations and battles of the Italian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cemetery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2014}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Anzio War Cemetery\n| image       = Anzio Cimitero Britannico by-RaBoe 031.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| established = \n| country     = [[Italy]]\n| location    = [[Anzio]], [[Lazio]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.456|12.623|display=inline}}\n| type        = \n| style       =\n| owner       = [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n| size        = \n| graves      = 1,056\n| interments  = \n| cremations  = \n| leases      = \n| website     = [http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/2064800/ANZIO%20WAR%20CEMETERY CWGC official website]\n| findagraveid= 2185816\n}}\n__NOTOC__\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Anzio-War-Cemetery.jpg|1000px|thumb|The Anzio War Cemetery.{{ifdc|Image:Anzio-War-Cemetery.jpg|log=2008 June 12}}]] -->\nThe [[Commonwealth of Nations]] '''Anzio War Cemetery''' is to be found about a kilometer from [[Anzio]] town in the [[Lazio]] region of [[Italy]]. It is located {{convert|70|km|abbr=off}} south of [[Rome]]. It should not be confused with the [[Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial]], which is for Americans and is located in [[Nettuno]] at the address \"Piazzale Kennedy, 1\".\n\n==Description and history==\nAnzio War Cemetery is a special and communal cemetery for the local and surrounding peoples. It contains 1,056 graves resulting from [[Operation Shingle]] in 1944 as part of [[World War II]]. Having seen the make up of the [[1st Canadian Division]] which was sent there in 1944 it is clear from the graves that those who rest there were from the units of the 1st Division. There were 1,037 identified casualties.\n\n;Poem\nThere is poem about the Anzio War Cemetery written by Michael Elliott-Binns.<ref name=\"Poem\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.salamanderoasis.org/poems/e/elliott-binns-michael/anziowarcemetery.html |title=Salamander Oasis}}</ref> It is written from the perspective of a man that had experienced a loss in the battle and that was writing for his own personal reasons.<ref name=\"Poem\"/> The author later commented that \"They [the fallen soldiers] seem to be buried on the doorstep of their home.\"<ref name=\"Poem\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.remembrancedaysong.com/ Image references]\n{{Portal bar|Architecture|Italy|World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Burials in Lazio]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in Italy]]\n[[Category:World War II operations and battles of the Italian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cemetery-stub}}\n", "name_user": "A.Petrenko", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anzio_War_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "It Comes at Night", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = It Comes at Night\n| image          = It Comes at Night.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Trey Edward Shults]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* David Kaplan\n* Andrea Roa\n}}\n| writer         = Trey Edward Shults\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Joel Edgerton]]\n* [[Christopher Abbott]]\n* [[Carmen Ejogo]]\n* [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]]\n* [[Riley Keough]]\n}}\n| music          = Brian McOmber\n| cinematography = Drew Daniels\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Trey Edward Shults\n* Matthew Hannam\n}}\n| studio         = \n{{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n* Animal Kingdom\n}}\n| distributor    = A24\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|4|29|[[Timberline Lodge]]|2017|6|9|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marsfilms.com/film/it-comes-at-night/|title=''It Comes at Night''|website=Mars Distribution|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/it-comes-night-film | title=''It Comes at Night'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2.4\u20135 million<ref>{{cite web|last1=Knapp|first1=JD|title=Box Office: \u2018Wonder Woman\u2019 Whips Up Another Win, \u2018The Mummy\u2019 DOA|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/mummy-wonder-woman-box-office-tom-cruise-universal-1202461516/|website=Variety|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=opening/>\n| gross          = $19.7 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/It-Comes-at-Night|title=It Comes at Night (2017) - Financial Information|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''It Comes at Night''''' is a 2017 American [[horror film]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/joel-edgerton-hopes-it-comes-at-night-will-help-improve-horror-s-reputation-247|title=Joel Edgerton hopes ''It Comes at Night'' will help improve horror's reputation|work=[[Joblo]]|first=Cody|last=Hamman|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> written and directed by [[Trey Edward Shults]]. It stars [[Joel Edgerton]], [[Christopher Abbott]], [[Carmen Ejogo]], [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]], and [[Riley Keough]].\n\nThe film had its premiere at the Overlook Film Festival at [[Timberline Lodge]] in [[Oregon]] on April 29, 2017, and was theatrically released on June 9, 2017 in the United States, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. It was positively received by critics and grossed over $19 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\nA highly contagious outbreak ravages the planet. Paul, his wife Sarah, and their teenage son Travis are secluded in their [[Retreat (survivalism)|home deep in the woods]] in an undisclosed location. After Sarah's father, Bud, contracts the disease, they kill him, and burn his body in a shallow grave. The next night, they capture an intruder breaking into the house. Paul ties him to a tree, and places a bag over his head overnight to confirm he is not suffering from the disease. The stranger, Will, explains he did not know the house was occupied, and was searching for fresh water for his wife and his young son. Will offers to trade some of their food for water. Sarah suggests bringing the strangers to their home, reasoning the more people, the easier it would be to defend themselves.  Paul reluctantly agrees, and drives Will to collect his family. Along the way, they are ambushed by two men. Paul kills them, while accusing Will of setting him up. Will explains he fought them, and assuages Paul's mistrust.\n\nPaul returns with Will, his wife Kim, and son Andrew. After establishing the rules Paul and Sarah use to stay safe, including a) keeping the only entrance locked with a key Paul or Sarah wear around their neck, and b)  keeping nighttime excursions to a minimum, the two families establish a sense of normality, and grow closer. One day, Travis's dog Stanley is barking aggressively at and chases an unseen presence in the woods. Travis follows the dog into the woods before Stanley's barking suddenly ceases. Travis insists to Paul and Will he heard something in the woods. They return home after Paul assures Travis that Stanley knows the woods and will find his way home. That night, Will seemingly contradicts a story he told Paul earlier about his and Kim's activities prior to finding the abandoned house. Paul's response suggests an increasing distrust of Will. \n\nThat evening, Travis discovers Andrew sleeping on the floor of Bud's old room suffering from a nightmare. Travis leads him back to his parents' room before hearing a sound from downstairs. Travis finds the front door of the house is slightly-open, and he hears noises. He wakes Paul and Will. They investigate, finding a bleeding and gravely-sick Stanley on the floor. They kill and burn the dog. After Travis reveals the door was open before he came downstairs, Sarah suggests sleepwalking Andrew opened the door. Kim argues the possibility as tensions rise. Paul suspects Andrew is infected, and decides they should quarantine in their separate rooms for a couple days so they can calm down and ensure no one is sick. That evening, Travis is awakened by a nightmare about his grandfather.\n\nThe next morning, Travis overhears Andrew coughing constantly. A distraught Kim tells Will they need to leave. Travis informs his parents Andrew might be infected, and, as such, he too may be infected. Paul and Sarah don protective masks and gloves, and take weapons to confront Kim and Will. After Paul asks to be let in to see if Andrew is sick, Will draws a gun and takes Paul captive. Will insists his family is healthy, repeatedly tells Andrew to keep his eyes shut and orders Paul to remove the mask. Will demands Paul give him \"...a fair share...\" of food and water so they can leave. Paul and Sarah overwhelm Will, and force him and his family outside.  Will attacks Paul, and tries to beat him to death as Sarah shoots Will in the back. He dies from his wound. Kim flees into the woods with Andrew. Paul fires at them, killing Andrew. Kim hysterically begs Paul to kill her to end her misery, and he does by shooting her.\n\nLater, Travis awakens in bed, visibly sick. His mother comforts him as he dies. Paul and Sarah, now visibly infected, sit at the dinner table in silence. They share a shattered, devastated look.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--In order as final credits-->\n* [[Joel Edgerton]] as Paul, Sarah\u2019s husband and Travis\u2019s father\n* [[Christopher Abbott]] as Will, Kim\u2019s husband and Andrew\u2019s father\n* [[Carmen Ejogo]] as Sarah, Paul\u2019s wife and Travis\u2019s mother\n* [[Riley Keough]] as Kim, Will\u2019s wife and Andrew\u2019s mother\n* [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]] as Travis, Paul and Sarah\u2019s son\n* Griffin Robert Faulkner as Andrew, Will and Kim\u2019s son\n* David Pendleton as Bud, Sarah's father and Travis\u2019s grandfather\n* Mickey as Stanley, the family dog\n* Chase Joliet and Mick O'Rourke as men who attack Paul and Will\n\n==Production==\nShults began writing the film after the death of his father as a way of dealing with the pain.<ref name=\"Slashfilm\"/> He cites [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]]\u2019s 1562 oil painting ''[[The Triumph of Death]]'' as inspiration and it features prominently in the movie and its first trailer.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite web|last=Stevens|first=Dana|title=slate.com|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2017/06/it_comes_at_night_the_new_horror_movie_reviewed.html|website=It Comes at Night|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|last1=Collin|first1=Robbie|title=It Comes At Night review: the end of the world has never been more gripping|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/comes-night-review-end-world-has-never-gripping/|website=telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|last1=McGovern|first1=Joe|title=ew.com|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/09/it-comes-at-night-director-influences/|website=It Comes at Night director shares 10 influences, from Kubrick to video games|publisher=Time Inc|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref> Although the film is [[post-apocalyptic]] Shults did not look to any other such films as inspiration; instead, he cited the work of [[Paul Thomas Anderson]] and [[John Cassavetes]] and the films ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' and ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' as inspirations. To the later point, the film takes some influences from ''The Shining''{{'}}s [[Overlook Hotel]] in that the layout of the house is deliberately vague and never properly established. Shults has described it \"as this kind of labyrinth\" and a metaphor for \"the mesh of Travis' head\".<ref name=\"Slashfilm\">{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Jacob|title=\u2018It Comes at Night\u2019 Director Trey Edward Shults on How \u2018The Shining\u2019 Inspired His New Cinematic Nightmare [Interview]|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/it-comes-at-night-trey-edward-shults-interview/|website=/Film|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, [[Joel Edgerton]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/joel-edgerton-it-comes-at-night-trey-edwards-smith-a24-1201770393/|title=Joel Edgerton In Talks For Thriller \u2018It Comes At Night\u2019 By \u2018Krisha\u2019 Helmer Trey Edward Shults|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Ali|last=Jafaar|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/joel-edgerton-it-comes-at-night-1201793104/|title=Joel Edgerton Joins Thriller \u2018It Comes at Night\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref> In August 2016, it was announced that [[Christopher Abbott]], [[Riley Keough]] and [[Carmen Ejogo]] had also joined the cast.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/jon-bernthal-christopher-abbott-imogen-poots-join-thriller-sweet-virginia-xyz-films-1201806997/|title=Jon Bernthal, Imogen Poots & Others Join Thriller \u2018Sweet Virginia\u2019|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=August 22, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began in August 2016 in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moveablefest.com/moveable_fest/2016/09/wayne-roberts-katie-says-goodbye.html|title=TIFF \u201916 INTERVIEW: WAYNE ROBERTS ON MAKING QUITE THE ENTRANCE WITH \"KATIE SAYS GOODBYE\"|website=Moveable Fest|first=Stephen|last=Saito|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914021220/http://moveablefest.com/moveable_fest/2016/09/wayne-roberts-katie-says-goodbye.html|archive-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at The Overlook Film Festival at [[Timberline Lodge]], [[Oregon]], on April 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/04/it-comes-at-night-secret-premiere-trey-shults-overlook-film-festival-1201810327/|title=\u2018It Comes at Night\u2019 Makes A Surprise Appearance at New Horror Festival|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=April 29, 2017|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> The film was scheduled to be released on August 25, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/A24/status/828624765481054211|title=On August 25th... #ItComesAtNight|website=[[Twitter.com]]|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> but was rescheduled for June 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://a24films.com/films/it-comes-at-night/|title=It Comes at Night|website=[[A24 (company)|A24]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''It Comes at Night'' grossed $14 million in the United States and Canada and $5.7 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $19.7 million.<ref name=\"numbers\" />\n\n''It Comes at Night'' was released alongside ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' and ''[[Megan Leavey (film)|Megan Leavey]]'', and was expected to gross around $7 million from 2,533 theaters in its opening weekend, with a chance of making as much as $12 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-mummy-wonder-woman20170606-htmlstory.html|title=Tom Cruise's 'The Mummy' faces tough box-office battle against 'Wonder Woman|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> It made $700,000 from Thursday night previews and $2.4 million on its first day. It ended up debuting to $6 million, finishing 6th at the box office. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' noted the film's poor audience word-of-mouth led to a drop of potential Saturday and Sunday sales.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/wonder-woman-beats-tom-cruise-mummy-at-the-box-office-1202110164/|title=Why \u2018The Mummy\u2019 Turned Crummy At The Domestic B.O. & What This Means For Uni\u2019s \u2018Dark Universe|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=June 10, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 240 reviews, with an [[arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 7.38/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''It Comes at Night'' makes lethally effective use of its bare-bones trappings while proving once again that what's left unseen can be just as horrifying as anything on the screen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_comes_at_night|title=It Comes at Night (2017)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score 78 out of 100, based on 43 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it-comes-at-night|title=It Comes at Night Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive|CBS Interactive Inc.]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=opening/>\n\nBrian Tallerico of [[RogerEbert.com]] gives the horror film a thumbs up.  He says \"It is a movie in which the villains are loss, grief, pain, fear and distrust \u2014 very human emotions \u2014 and it has no traditional brain-eaters.\" And he adds that \"it is one of the most terrifying film in years\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com//reviews//it-comes-at-night-2017|title=It Comes at Night|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|date=June 9, 2017|website=www.RogerEbert.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Table to prose|section|date=April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards]]\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2017|November 27, 2017]]\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Breakthrough Actor]]\n| [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|last=Erbland|first=Kate|title=\u2018Get Out\u2019 Leads 2017 Gotham Awards Nominations|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/gotham-awards-nominations-2017-1202594047/|accessdate=19 October 2017|work=IndieWire|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Retreat (film)|Retreat]]'', a film with some similiar details in its plot.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4695012}}\n* {{allmovie title}}\n* {{Mojo title|itcomesatnight}}\n* {{Metacritic film|it-comes-at-night}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|it_comes_at_night}}\n\n{{Trey Edward Shults}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:Films about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Trey Edward Shults]]\n[[Category:Films set in forests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = It Comes at Night\n| image          = It Comes at Night.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Trey Edward Shults]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* David Kaplan\n* Andrea Roa\n}}\n| writer         = Trey Edward Shults\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Joel Edgerton]]\n* [[Christopher Abbott]]\n* [[Carmen Ejogo]]\n* [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]]\n* [[Riley Keough]]\n}}\n| music          = Brian McOmber\n| cinematography = Drew Daniels\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Trey Edward Shults\n* Matthew Hannam\n}}\n| studio         = \n{{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n* Animal Kingdom\n}}\n| distributor    = A24\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|4|29|[[Timberline Lodge]]|2017|6|9|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marsfilms.com/film/it-comes-at-night/|title=''It Comes at Night''|website=Mars Distribution|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/it-comes-night-film | title=''It Comes at Night'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2.4\u20135 million<ref>{{cite web|last1=Knapp|first1=JD|title=Box Office: \u2018Wonder Woman\u2019 Whips Up Another Win, \u2018The Mummy\u2019 DOA|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/mummy-wonder-woman-box-office-tom-cruise-universal-1202461516/|website=Variety|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=opening/>\n| gross          = $19.7 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/It-Comes-at-Night|title=It Comes at Night (2017) - Financial Information|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''It Comes at Night''''' is a 2017 American [[horror film]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/joel-edgerton-hopes-it-comes-at-night-will-help-improve-horror-s-reputation-247|title=Joel Edgerton hopes ''It Comes at Night'' will help improve horror's reputation|work=[[Joblo]]|first=Cody|last=Hamman|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> written and directed by [[Trey Edward Shults]]. It stars [[Joel Edgerton]], [[Christopher Abbott]], [[Carmen Ejogo]], [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]], and [[Riley Keough]].\n\nThe film had its premiere at the Overlook Film Festival at [[Timberline Lodge]] in [[Oregon]] on April 29, 2017, and was theatrically released on June 9, 2017 in the United States, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. It was positively received by critics and grossed over $19 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\nA highly contagious outbreak ravages the planet. Paul, his wife Sarah, and their teenage son Travis are secluded in their [[Retreat (survivalism)|home deep in the woods]] in an undisclosed location. After Sarah's father, Bud, contracts the disease, they kill him, and burn his body in a shallow grave. The next night, they capture an intruder breaking into the house. Paul ties him to a tree, and places a bag over his head overnight to confirm he is not suffering from the disease. The stranger, Will, explains he did not know the house was occupied, and was searching for fresh water for his wife and his young son. Will offers to trade some of their food for water. Sarah suggests bringing the strangers to their home, reasoning the more people, the easier it would be to defend themselves.  Paul reluctantly agrees, and drives Will to collect his family. Along the way, they are ambushed by two men. Paul kills them, while accusing Will of setting him up. Will explains he fought them, and assuages Paul's mistrust.\n\nPaul returns with Will, his wife Kim, and son Andrew. After establishing the rules Paul and Sarah use to stay safe, including a) keeping the only entrance locked with a key Paul or Sarah wear around their neck, and b)  keeping nighttime excursions to a minimum, the two families establish a sense of normality, and grow closer. One day, Travis's dog Stanley is barking aggressively at and chases an unseen presence in the woods. Travis follows the dog into the woods before Stanley's barking suddenly ceases. Travis insists to Paul and Will he heard something in the woods. They return home after Paul assures Travis that Stanley knows the woods and will find his way home. That night, Will seemingly contradicts a story he told Paul earlier about his and Kim's activities prior to finding the abandoned house. Paul's response suggests an increasing distrust of Will. \n\nThat evening, Travis discovers Andrew sleeping on the floor of Bud's old room suffering from a nightmare. Travis leads him back to his parents' room before hearing a sound from downstairs. Travis finds the front door of the house is slightly-open, and he hears noises. He wakes Paul and Will. They investigate, finding a bleeding and gravely-sick Stanley on the floor. They kill and burn the dog. After Travis reveals the door was open before he came downstairs, Sarah suggests sleepwalking Andrew opened the door. Kim argues the possibility as tensions rise. Paul suspects Andrew is infected, and decides they should quarantine in their separate rooms for a couple days so they can calm down and ensure no one is sick. That evening, Travis is awakened by a nightmare about his grandfather.\n\nThe next morning, Travis overhears Andrew coughing constantly. A distraught Kim tells Will they need to leave. Travis informs his parents Andrew might be infected, and, as such, he too may be infected. Paul and Sarah don protective masks and gloves, and take weapons to confront Kim and Will. After Paul asks to be let in to see if Andrew is sick, Will draws a gun and takes Paul captive. Will insists his family is healthy, repeatedly tells Andrew to keep his eyes shut and orders Paul to remove the mask. Will demands Paul give him \"...a fair share...\" of food and water so they can leave. Paul and Sarah overwhelm Will, and force him and his family outside.  Will attacks Paul, and tries to beat him to death as Sarah shoots Will in the back. He dies from his wound. Kim flees into the woods with Andrew. Paul fires at them, killing Andrew. Kim hysterically begs Paul to kill her to end her misery, and he does by shooting her.\n\nLater, Travis awakens in bed, visibly sick. His mother comforts him as he dies. Paul and Sarah, now visibly infected, sit at the dinner table in silence. They share a shattered, devastated look.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--In order as final credits-->\n* [[Joel Edgerton]] as Paul, Sarah\u2019s husband and Travis\u2019s father\n* [[Christopher Abbott]] as Will, Kim\u2019s husband and Andrew\u2019s father\n* [[Carmen Ejogo]] as Sarah, Paul\u2019s wife and Travis\u2019s mother\n* [[Riley Keough]] as Kim, Will\u2019s wife and Andrew\u2019s mother\n* [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]] as Travis, Paul and Sarah\u2019s son\n* Griffin Robert Faulkner as Andrew, Will and Kim\u2019s son\n* David Pendleton as Bud, Sarah's father and Travis\u2019s grandfather\n* Mickey as Stanley, the family dog\n* Chase Joliet and Mick O'Rourke as men who attack Paul and Will\n\n==Production==\nShults began writing the film after the death of his father as a way of dealing with the pain.<ref name=\"Slashfilm\"/> He cites [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]]\u2019s 1562 oil painting ''[[The Triumph of Death]]'' as inspiration and it features prominently in the movie and its first trailer.<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite web|last=Stevens|first=Dana|title=slate.com|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2017/06/it_comes_at_night_the_new_horror_movie_reviewed.html|website=It Comes at Night|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|last1=Collin|first1=Robbie|title=It Comes At Night review: the end of the world has never been more gripping|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/comes-night-review-end-world-has-never-gripping/|website=telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|last1=McGovern|first1=Joe|title=ew.com|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/09/it-comes-at-night-director-influences/|website=It Comes at Night director shares 10 influences, from Kubrick to video games|publisher=Time Inc|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref> Although the film is [[post-apocalyptic]] Shults did not look to any other such films as inspiration; instead, he cited the work of [[Paul Thomas Anderson]] and [[John Cassavetes]] and the films ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' and ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' as inspirations. To the later point, the film takes some influences from ''The Shining''{{'}}s [[Overlook Hotel]] in that the layout of the house is deliberately vague and never properly established. Shults has described it \"as this kind of labyrinth\" and a metaphor for \"the mesh of Travis\u2019 head.\"<ref name=\"Slashfilm\">{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Jacob|title=\u2018It Comes at Night\u2019 Director Trey Edward Shults on How \u2018The Shining\u2019 Inspired His New Cinematic Nightmare [Interview]|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/it-comes-at-night-trey-edward-shults-interview/|website=/Film|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, [[Joel Edgerton]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/joel-edgerton-it-comes-at-night-trey-edwards-smith-a24-1201770393/|title=Joel Edgerton In Talks For Thriller \u2018It Comes At Night\u2019 By \u2018Krisha\u2019 Helmer Trey Edward Shults|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Ali|last=Jafaar|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/joel-edgerton-it-comes-at-night-1201793104/|title=Joel Edgerton Joins Thriller \u2018It Comes at Night\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref> In August 2016, it was announced that [[Christopher Abbott]], [[Riley Keough]] and [[Carmen Ejogo]] had also joined the cast.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/jon-bernthal-christopher-abbott-imogen-poots-join-thriller-sweet-virginia-xyz-films-1201806997/|title=Jon Bernthal, Imogen Poots & Others Join Thriller \u2018Sweet Virginia\u2019|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=August 22, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began in August 2016 in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moveablefest.com/moveable_fest/2016/09/wayne-roberts-katie-says-goodbye.html|title=TIFF \u201916 INTERVIEW: WAYNE ROBERTS ON MAKING QUITE THE ENTRANCE WITH \"KATIE SAYS GOODBYE\"|website=Moveable Fest|first=Stephen|last=Saito|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914021220/http://moveablefest.com/moveable_fest/2016/09/wayne-roberts-katie-says-goodbye.html|archive-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at The Overlook Film Festival at [[Timberline Lodge]], [[Oregon]], on April 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/04/it-comes-at-night-secret-premiere-trey-shults-overlook-film-festival-1201810327/|title=\u2018It Comes at Night\u2019 Makes A Surprise Appearance at New Horror Festival|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=April 29, 2017|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> The film was scheduled to be released on August 25, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/A24/status/828624765481054211|title=On August 25th... #ItComesAtNight|website=[[Twitter.com]]|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> but was rescheduled for June 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://a24films.com/films/it-comes-at-night/|title=It Comes at Night|website=[[A24 (company)|A24]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''It Comes at Night'' grossed $14 million in the United States and Canada and $5.7 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $19.7 million.<ref name=\"numbers\" />\n\n''It Comes at Night'' was released alongside ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' and ''[[Megan Leavey (film)|Megan Leavey]]'', and was expected to gross around $7 million from 2,533 theaters in its opening weekend, with a chance of making as much as $12 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-mummy-wonder-woman20170606-htmlstory.html|title=Tom Cruise's 'The Mummy' faces tough box-office battle against 'Wonder Woman|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> It made $700,000 from Thursday night previews and $2.4 million on its first day. It ended up debuting to $6 million, finishing 6th at the box office. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' noted the film's poor audience word-of-mouth led to a drop of potential Saturday and Sunday sales.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/wonder-woman-beats-tom-cruise-mummy-at-the-box-office-1202110164/|title=Why \u2018The Mummy\u2019 Turned Crummy At The Domestic B.O. & What This Means For Uni\u2019s \u2018Dark Universe|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=June 10, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 240 reviews, with an [[arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 7.38/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''It Comes at Night'' makes lethally effective use of its bare-bones trappings while proving once again that what's left unseen can be just as horrifying as anything on the screen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_comes_at_night|title=It Comes at Night (2017)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score 78 out of 100, based on 43 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it-comes-at-night|title=It Comes at Night Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive|CBS Interactive Inc.]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=opening/>\n\nBrian Tallerico of [[RogerEbert.com]] gives the horror film a thumbs up.  He says \"It is a movie in which the villains are loss, grief, pain, fear and distrust--very human emotions--and it has no traditional brain-eaters.\"   And he adds \"...it is one of the most terrifying film in years.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com//reviews//it-comes-at-night-2017|title=It Comes at Night|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|date=June 9, 2017|website=www.RogerEbert.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Table to prose|section|date=April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards]]\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2017|November 27, 2017]]\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Breakthrough Actor]]\n| [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|last=Erbland|first=Kate|title=\u2018Get Out\u2019 Leads 2017 Gotham Awards Nominations|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/gotham-awards-nominations-2017-1202594047/|accessdate=19 October 2017|work=IndieWire|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Retreat (film)|Retreat]]'', a film with some similiar details in its plot.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4695012}}\n* {{allmovie title}}\n* {{Mojo title|itcomesatnight}}\n* {{Metacritic film|it-comes-at-night}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|it_comes_at_night}}\n\n{{Trey Edward Shults}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:Films about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Trey Edward Shults]]\n[[Category:Films set in forests]]\n", "name_user": "Chocolateboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "logical quotation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It_Comes_at_Night"}
{"title_page": "WikiHouse", "text_new": "[[File:Wikihouse The Hub Westminster.jpg|thumb|WikiHouse prototype in [[Westminster]]]]\n\n'''WikiHouse''' is an [[open-source hardware|open-source]] project for designing and building [[house]]s.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/> It endeavours to democratise and simplify the construction of sustainable, resource-light dwellings.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/><ref name=Borgobello/><ref name=Isaacson/><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://jfsdigital.org/articles-and-essays/2018-2/the-emergence-of-open-construction-systems-a-sustainable-paradigm-in-the-construction-sector/|title=The Emergence of Open Construction Systems: A Sustainable Paradigm in the Construction Sector?|last=|first=|date=2019-01-14|website=Journal of Futures Studies|pages=67\u201384|language=en-US|doi=10.6531/jfs.201812_23(2).0005|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> The project was initiated in the summer of 2011 by [[Alastair Parvin]] and Nick Ierodiaconou of 00, a London-based strategy and design practice, in collaboration with Tav of Espians, James Arthur now with 00 and Steve Fisher of Momentum Engineering.<ref name=Parvin/><ref name=Firth/> It was launched at the [[Gwangju Design Biennale]] in [[Gwangju]], [[South Korea]].<ref name=Parvin>{{cite web|last=Parvin|first=Alastair|title=A House and Home for the 99%|url=http://www.thecity2.org/stories/a-house-and-home-for-the-99/|work=CITY2.0|publisher=[[TED (conference)|TED Conferences, LLC]]|accessdate=17 December 2013|author2=Nick Ierodiaconou |date=22 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Hicks\">{{cite web|last = Hicks|first = Jesse|title = WikiHouse promises printable homes, work for the world's idle CNC routers|url = https://www.engadget.com/2011/08/17/wikihouse-promises-printable-homes-work-for-the-worlds-idle-cn/|work = [[Engadget]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=00Blog>{{cite web|title=00:/ at TED2013|url=http://www.architecture00.net/blog/?p=2832|work=00:/Blog|publisher=00:/|accessdate=20 December 2013|date=27 February 2013}}</ref> The project has since grown to become a worldwide community of contributors.<ref name=\"WikiHouse Community\">{{cite web|title = WikiHouse Community|url = http://www.wikihouse.cc/community|publisher = WikiHouse|accessdate = 20 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Concept ==\n[[File:Scale model of WikiHouse system 1.0 and 2.0.jpg|thumb|[[Scale model]]s of two different WikiHouse designs]]\n\nWikiHouse enables users to download [[Creative Commons]]-licensed building plans from its online library, customize them using [[SketchUp]], and then use them to create [[jigsaw puzzle]]-like pieces out of [[plywood]] with a [[CNC router]].<ref name=LaBarre>{{cite web|last=LaBarre|first=Suzanne|title=WikiHouse, An Online Building Kit, Shows How To Make A House In 24 Hours|url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664873/wikihouse-an-online-building-kit-shows-how-to-make-a-house-in-24-hours|work=Co.Design|publisher=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company, Inc]]|accessdate=17 December 2013|date=25 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Firth\">{{cite web|last = Firth|first = Peter|title = Grand Designs: Open-source platform comes to housing|url = http://www.lsnglobal.com/seed/view/4268|work = <nowiki>LifeStyle:News:Global</nowiki>|accessdate = 17 December 2013|author2 = Thomas Rees|date = 5 August 2011}}</ref> Construction of WikiHouse structures requires no special parts because the cut pieces of wood snap together with wedge and peg connections inspired by classical [[Korean architecture]].<ref name=\"McNicoll\">{{cite web|last = McNicoll|first = Arion|title = How to build your home from scratch for $35,000|url = http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/01/tech/wikihouse-build-your-own-house/index.html|work = [[CNN|CNN.com]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 5 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodwins\">{{cite web|last = Goodwins|first = Rupert|title = Meet The People Who Want To Print A Home In A Day|url = http://www.popsci.com/article/technology/meet-people-who-want-print-home-day|work = [[Popular Science]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|authorlink = Rupert Goodwins|date = 16 December 2013}}</ref> The frame of a WikiHouse can be assembled in less than a day by people with no formal training in construction.<ref name=McNicoll/> The frame must then be finished with [[cladding (construction)|cladding]], [[building insulation|insulation]], [[electrical wiring|wiring]], and [[plumbing]] before it can be inhabited.<ref name=\"Kingsley\">{{cite web|last = Kingsley|first = Jeremy|title = The WikiHouse Revolution|url = http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/future_tense/2012/02/wikihouse_the_diy_movement_and_architectural_innovation_.html|work = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 22 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Goodwins/> The WikiHouse project is maintained by [[Open Systems Lab]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensystemslab.io/Projects|title=Projects|publisher=Open Systems Labs|access-date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Ouisharefest - Wikihouse (8710423939).jpg|thumb|A WikiHouse under construction at ''Ouisharefest'' in [[Paris]], May 2013]]\n\nAfter winning a cash prize at [[TEDGlobal]] in June 2012, the project invested the prize money into a partnership with the Brazilian youth mobilization project Dharma and the analysis agency BrazilIntel to build WikiHouses in the poorest [[favela]]s of [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref name=Isaacson/> The goal of the partnership, dubbed WikiHouseRio, is to provide a single \"maker lab\" where one CNC router can be shared by the community while also allowing and encouraging community members to develop their own designing and building skills.<ref name=Isaacson/><ref name=Parvin/> The WikiHouse team plans to eventually create similar maker labs in other underdeveloped communities around the world.<ref name=Isaacson/> There are also plans to use WikiHouses as [[emergency management|disaster-relief]] housing in [[earthquake]]-prone countries such as [[Haiti]], [[Japan]], and [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"Borgobello\">{{cite web|last = Borgobello|first = Bridget|title = WikiHouse: Get ready to design, \"print\" and construct your own home!|url = http://www.gizmag.com/wikihouse-print-your-own-home-project/22548/|work = Gizmag|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 15 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2013, while there were no inhabited WikiHouses, there were a few completed prototypes in addition to a usable walkers' shelter in [[Fridaythorpe]], [[England]].<ref name=\"Goodwins\" /> These WikiHouses are single-story, square-shaped structures with sloped roofs and small foundations that measure about {{convert|175|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=\"Kingsley\" /> By 2015, several additional WikiHouses had been built, including the following buildings and at the following events:\n* [[Maker Faire]] 2013 in [[Queens]]<ref name=\"WikiHouse1\">{{cite web|title = WikiHouse Gives Architecture to the People|url = http://www.globallighting.com/wikihouse-gives-architecture-people/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 23 January 2014|website = Global Lighting}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse 4.0 at the [[London Design Festival]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.archdaily.com/550093/wikihouse-unveils-world-s-first-two-storey-open-source-house-at-london-design-festival|title=WikiHouse Unveils World's First Two-Storey Open-Source House at London Design Festival|last=Stott|first=Rory|date=September 22, 2014|work=[[ArchDaily]]|access-date=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* {{Convert|150|sqft|m2|adj = on}} FOUNDhouse microhouse<ref name=\"FOUNDhouse\">{{cite web|title = FOUNDhouse|url = http://foundhouse.cc|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = FOUNDhouse}}</ref><ref name=\"VermontWikiHouseDesignFiles\">{{cite web|title = WikihouseUS/Vermont-Microhouse|url = https://github.com/WikihouseUS/Vermont-Microhouse|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = [[GitHub]]}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse at MAKlab in [[Glasgow]]<ref name=\"MAKlabsWikiHouse\">{{cite web|title = MAKLab's Wikihouse: Day One|url = http://duncanbain.com/research/blog/maklabs-wikihouse-day-one/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 15 July 2013|website = Open Source Architecture blog|last = Bain|first = Duncan}}</ref> \n* Chop Shop in western [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"A-Barn\">{{cite web|title = Wikihouse|url = http://chopshopcnc.com/2014/10/wikihouse/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 23 October 2014|publisher = Chop Shop}}</ref> \n* Space Craft Systems project in New Zealand<ref name=\"Spacecraft\">{{cite web|title = Space Craft: developing WikiHouse in New Zealand|url = http://spacecraft.co.nz|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = Space Craft Systems}}</ref> \n* WikiSHED [[fork (software development)|fork]]<ref name=\"WikiSHED\">{{cite web|title = Wikihouse Project|url = http://www.sketchthis.net/blog/wikihouse-project|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 2 January 2014|website = SketchThis}}</ref><ref name=\"WikiSHEDDesignFiles\">{{cite web|title = WikihouseUS/Alex-Wikished|url = https://github.com/WikihouseUS/Alex-Wikished|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = [[GitHub]]}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse at the 2015 Vienna Open<ref name=\"WikiHouse Opening\">{{cite web|title = Vienna Open|url = http://viennaopen.net/events/eroffnung-wikihouse/|publisher = Vienna Open, Verlag Neue Arbeit|accessdate = 29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nMedia reaction to WikiHouse has focused largely on the experimental nature of the project,<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/> comparisons with [[IKEA]] furniture,<ref name=Kingsley/><ref name=Goodwins/> and the potential difficulty in finding and costs of using CNC routers.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=\"Isaacson\">{{cite web|last = Isaacson|first = Betsy|title = WikiHouse Democratizes Design For Inexpensive, Easily Built Homes|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/01/wikihouse-design-inexpensive-homes_n_2790860.html|work = [[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 1 March 2013}}</ref> American science fiction author [[Bruce Sterling]] also gave a review of the WikiHouse design, describing it favorably as a dwelling \"I could quite likely build and inhabit, personally\".<ref name=\"Sterling\">{{cite web|last = Sterling|first = Bruce|title = Architecture Fiction: WikiHouse|url = https://www.wired.com/beyond_the_beyond/2011/08/architecture-fiction-wikihouse/|work = [[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|authorlink = Bruce Sterling|date = 2 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Open-source architecture]]\n* [[Open-source hardware]]\n* [[List of open-source hardware projects]]\n* [[OpenDesk]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.wikihouse.cc/}}\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/alastair_parvin_architecture_for_the_people_by_the_people.html Alastair Parvin's TED Talk: Architecture for the people by the people]\n\n[[Category:Open-source hardware]]\n[[Category:Prefabricated houses]]\n[[Category:Open content projects]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wikihouse The Hub Westminster.jpg|thumb|WikiHouse prototype in [[Westminster]]]]\n\n'''WikiHouse''' is an [[open-source hardware|open-source]] project for designing and building [[house]]s.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/> It endeavours to democratise and simplify the construction of sustainable, resource-light dwellings.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/><ref name=Borgobello/><ref name=Isaacson/><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://jfsdigital.org/articles-and-essays/2018-2/the-emergence-of-open-construction-systems-a-sustainable-paradigm-in-the-construction-sector/|title=The Emergence of Open Construction Systems: A Sustainable Paradigm in the Construction Sector?|last=|first=|date=2019-01-14|website=Journal of Futures Studies|pages=67\u201384|language=en-US|doi=10.6531/jfs.201812_23(2).0005|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> The project was initiated in the summer of 2011 by [[Alastair Parvin]] and Nick Ierodiaconou of 00, a London-based strategy and design practice, in collaboration with Tav of Espians, James Arthur now with 00 and Steve Fisher of Momentum Engineering.<ref name=Parvin/><ref name=Firth/> It was launched at the [[Gwangju Design Biennale]] in [[Gwangju]], [[South Korea]].<ref name=Parvin>{{cite web|last=Parvin|first=Alastair|title=A House and Home for the 99%|url=http://www.thecity2.org/stories/a-house-and-home-for-the-99/|work=CITY2.0|publisher=[[TED (conference)|TED Conferences, LLC]]|accessdate=17 December 2013|author2=Nick Ierodiaconou |date=22 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Hicks\">{{cite web|last = Hicks|first = Jesse|title = WikiHouse promises printable homes, work for the world's idle CNC routers|url = https://www.engadget.com/2011/08/17/wikihouse-promises-printable-homes-work-for-the-worlds-idle-cn/|work = [[Engadget]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=00Blog>{{cite web|title=00:/ at TED2013|url=http://www.architecture00.net/blog/?p=2832|work=00:/Blog|publisher=00:/|accessdate=20 December 2013|date=27 February 2013}}</ref> The project has since grown to become a worldwide community of contributors.<ref name=\"WikiHouse Community\">{{cite web|title = WikiHouse Community|url = http://www.wikihouse.cc/community|publisher = WikiHouse|accessdate = 20 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Concept ==\n[[File:Scale model of WikiHouse system 1.0 and 2.0.jpg|thumb|[[Scale model]]s of two different WikiHouse designs]]\n\nWikiHouse enables users to download [[Creative Commons]]-licensed building plans from its online library, customize them using [[SketchUp]], and then use them to create [[jigsaw puzzle]]-like pieces out of [[plywood]] with a [[CNC router]].<ref name=LaBarre>{{cite web|last=LaBarre|first=Suzanne|title=WikiHouse, An Online Building Kit, Shows How To Make A House In 24 Hours|url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664873/wikihouse-an-online-building-kit-shows-how-to-make-a-house-in-24-hours|work=Co.Design|publisher=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company, Inc]]|accessdate=17 December 2013|date=25 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Firth\">{{cite web|last = Firth|first = Peter|title = Grand Designs: Open-source platform comes to housing|url = http://www.lsnglobal.com/seed/view/4268|work = <nowiki>LifeStyle:News:Global</nowiki>|accessdate = 17 December 2013|author2 = Thomas Rees|date = 5 August 2011}}</ref> Construction of WikiHouse structures requires no special parts because the cut pieces of wood snap together with wedge and peg connections inspired by classical [[Korean architecture]].<ref name=\"McNicoll\">{{cite web|last = McNicoll|first = Arion|title = How to build your home from scratch for $35,000|url = http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/01/tech/wikihouse-build-your-own-house/index.html|work = [[CNN|CNN.com]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 5 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodwins\">{{cite web|last = Goodwins|first = Rupert|title = Meet The People Who Want To Print A Home In A Day|url = http://www.popsci.com/article/technology/meet-people-who-want-print-home-day|work = [[Popular Science]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|authorlink = Rupert Goodwins|date = 16 December 2013}}</ref> The frame of a WikiHouse can be assembled in less than a day by people with no formal training in construction.<ref name=McNicoll/> The frame must then be finished with [[cladding (construction)|cladding]], [[building insulation|insulation]], [[electrical wiring|wiring]], and [[plumbing]] before it can be inhabited.<ref name=\"Kingsley\">{{cite web|last = Kingsley|first = Jeremy|title = The WikiHouse Revolution|url = http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/future_tense/2012/02/wikihouse_the_diy_movement_and_architectural_innovation_.html|work = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 22 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Goodwins/> The WikiHouse project is maintained by [[Open Systems Lab]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensystemslab.io/Projects|title=Projects|publisher=Open Systems Labs|access-date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Ouisharefest - Wikihouse (8710423939).jpg|thumb|A WikiHouse under construction at ''Ouisharefest'' in [[Paris]], May 2013]]\n\nAfter winning a cash prize at [[TEDGlobal]] in June 2012, the project invested the prize money into a partnership with the Brazilian youth mobilization project Dharma and the analysis agency BrazilIntel to build WikiHouses in the poorest [[favela]]s of [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref name=Isaacson/> The goal of the partnership, dubbed WikiHouseRio, is to provide a single \"maker lab\" where one CNC router can be shared by the community while also allowing and encouraging community members to develop their own designing and building skills.<ref name=Isaacson/><ref name=Parvin/> The WikiHouse team plans to eventually create similar maker labs in other underdeveloped communities around the world.<ref name=Isaacson/> There are also plans to use WikiHouses as [[emergency management|disaster-relief]] housing in [[earthquake]]-prone countries such as [[Haiti]], [[Japan]], and [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"Borgobello\">{{cite web|last = Borgobello|first = Bridget|title = WikiHouse: Get ready to design, \"print\" and construct your own home!|url = http://www.gizmag.com/wikihouse-print-your-own-home-project/22548/|work = Gizmag|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 15 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2013, while there were no inhabited WikiHouses, there were a few completed prototypes in addition to a usable walkers' shelter in [[Fridaythorpe]], [[England]].<ref name=\"Goodwins\" /> These WikiHouses are single-story, square-shaped structures with sloped roofs and small foundations that measure about {{convert|175|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=\"Kingsley\" /> By 2015, several additional WikiHouses had been built, including the following buildings and at the following events:\n* [[Maker Faire]] 2013 in [[Queens]]<ref name=\"WikiHouse1\">{{cite web|title = WikiHouse Gives Architecture to the People|url = http://www.globallighting.com/wikihouse-gives-architecture-people/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 23 January 2014|website = Global Lighting}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse 4.0 at the [[London Design Festival]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.archdaily.com/550093/wikihouse-unveils-world-s-first-two-storey-open-source-house-at-london-design-festival|title=WikiHouse Unveils World's First Two-Storey Open-Source House at London Design Festival|last=Stott|first=Rory|date=September 22, 2014|work=[[ArchDaily]]|access-date=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* {{Convert|150|sqft|m2|adj = on}} FOUNDhouse microhouse<ref name=\"FOUNDhouse\">{{cite web|title = FOUNDhouse|url = http://foundhouse.cc|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = FOUNDhouse}}</ref><ref name=\"VermontWikiHouseDesignFiles\">{{cite web|title = WikihouseUS/Vermont-Microhouse|url = https://github.com/WikihouseUS/Vermont-Microhouse|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = [[GitHub]]}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse at MAKlab in [[Glasgow]]<ref name=\"MAKlabsWikiHouse\">{{cite web|title = MAKLab's Wikihouse: Day One|url = http://duncanbain.com/research/blog/maklabs-wikihouse-day-one/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 15 July 2013|website = Open Source Architecture blog|last = Bain|first = Duncan}}</ref> \n* Chop Shop in western [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"A-Barn\">{{cite web|title = Wikihouse|url = http://chopshopcnc.com/2014/10/wikihouse/|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 23 October 2014|publisher = Chop Shop}}</ref> \n* Space Craft Systems project in New Zealand<ref name=\"Spacecraft\">{{cite web|title = Space Craft: developing WikiHouse in New Zealand|url = http://spacecraft.co.nz|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = Space Craft Systems}}</ref> \n* WikiSHED [[fork (software development)|fork]]<ref name=\"WikiSHED\">{{cite web|title = Wikihouse Project|url = http://www.sketchthis.net/blog/wikihouse-project|accessdate = 13 April 2015|date = 2 January 2014|website = SketchThis}}</ref><ref name=\"WikiSHEDDesignFiles\">{{cite web|title = WikihouseUS/Alex-Wikished|url = https://github.com/WikihouseUS/Alex-Wikished|accessdate = 13 April 2015|publisher = [[GitHub]]}}</ref> \n* WikiHouse at the 2015 Vienna Open<ref name=\"WikiHouse Opening\">{{cite web|title = Vienna Open|url = http://viennaopen.net/events/eroffnung-wikihouse/|publisher = Vienna Open, Verlag Neue Arbeit|accessdate = 29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nMedia reaction to WikiHouse has focused largely on the experimental nature of the project,<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=Kingsley/> comparisons with [[IKEA]] furniture,<ref name=Kingsley/><ref name=Goodwins/> and the potential difficulty in finding and costs of using CNC routers.<ref name=LaBarre/><ref name=\"Isaacson\">{{cite web|last = Isaacson|first = Betsy|title = WikiHouse Democratizes Design For Inexpensive, Easily Built Homes|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/01/wikihouse-design-inexpensive-homes_n_2790860.html|work = [[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|date = 1 March 2013}}</ref> However, research has shown that once there is an engaged community with a strong supporting network around a WikiHouse, the level of conviviality may be high, overcoming potential barriers that would otherwise hinder its construction. American science fiction author [[Bruce Sterling]] also gave a review of the WikiHouse design, describing it favorably as a dwelling \"I could quite likely build and inhabit, personally\".<ref name=\"Sterling\">{{cite web|last = Sterling|first = Bruce|title = Architecture Fiction: WikiHouse|url = https://www.wired.com/beyond_the_beyond/2011/08/architecture-fiction-wikihouse/|work = [[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate = 17 December 2013|authorlink = Bruce Sterling|date = 2 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Open-source architecture]]\n* [[Open-source hardware]]\n* [[List of open-source hardware projects]]\n* [[OpenDesk]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.wikihouse.cc/}}\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/alastair_parvin_architecture_for_the_people_by_the_people.html Alastair Parvin's TED Talk: Architecture for the people by the people]\n\n[[Category:Open-source hardware]]\n[[Category:Prefabricated houses]]\n[[Category:Open content projects]]\n", "name_user": "Michael Barera", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImpact:removing sentence that was supported by the citation just removed asCITESPAM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WikiHouse"}
{"title_page": "Ned Lyons", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n\n|name          = Ned Lyons\n|image         = [[File:Ned Lyons from Byrnes \"Professional Criminals of America\".jpg|thumb|Ned Lyons recuperating in a hospital after being shot by police]]\n|birth_name    = Edward Lyons\n|birth_date    = 1839\n|birth_place   = [[Ireland]]\n|death_date    = 1906\n|death_place   = [[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]], US\n|nationality   = [[Irish-American]]\n|other_names   = Robert E. Hapgood, Edward T. Sanman, George Jackson  and George F. Lenning \n|known_for     = New York burglar, bank robber and underworld figure\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = Criminal\n|home_town     = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|successor     = \n|party         = \n|boards        = \n|spouse        = [[Sophie Lyons]] (wife)\n|partner       = \n|children      = 3 sons, 3 daughters\n|parents       = \n|relations     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Edward \"Ned\" Lyons''' was a [[New York City]] [[gangster]] in the 19th century. Born in Ireland around 1839, he immigrated to America as a child and settled in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]]. A burglar and bank robber, he learned his criminal trade in [[New York City]]. He was sentenced to [[Sing Sing Prison]], from which he escaped in 1872 with his wife, [[Sophie Lyons]]. After serving multiple prison terms he became a notorious hustler and [[Confidence trick|conman]].\n\nNed learned to understand how people think and react, and although impaired by extreme [[near-sightedness]], he was capable of quickly identifying liars, earning himself a high powered position among the gangs of New York.  Physically, he had a strikingly large head.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Asbury, Henry. ''The French Quarter: An Informal History of the New Orleans Underworld''. New York: Alfred A. Knoff, 1936. {{ISBN|1-56025-494-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.trove.net/MACA0001/MACA0001_001391.html Heliotype], showing Lyons in state\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040907093928/http://www.geocities.com/Heartland/Fields/4791/june1884.html The Willimantic Chronicle - Year of 1884], imprisoned at Springfield\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyons, Ned}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Gang members of New York City]]\n[[Category:Escapees from New York (state) detention]]\n[[Category:Criminals from New York City]]\n\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ned Lyons\n|birth_name    = Edward Lyons\n|birth_date    = 1839\n|birth_place   = [[Ireland]]\n|death_date    = 1906\n|death_place   = [[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]], US\n|nationality   = [[Irish-American]]\n|other_names   = Robert E. Hapgood, Edward T. Sanman, George Jackson  and George F. Lenning \n|known_for     = New York burglar, bank robber and underworld figure\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = Criminal\n|home_town     = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|successor     = \n|party         = \n|boards        = \n|spouse        = [[Sophie Lyons]] (wife)\n|partner       = \n|children      = 3 sons, 3 daughters\n|parents       = \n|relations     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Edward \"Ned\" Lyons''' was a [[New York City]] [[gangster]] in the 19th century. Born in Ireland around 1839, he immigrated to America as a child and settled in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]]. A burglar and bank robber, he learned his criminal trade in [[New York City]]. He was sentenced to [[Sing Sing Prison]], from which he escaped in 1872 with his wife, [[Sophie Lyons]]. After serving multiple prison terms he became a notorious hustler and [[Confidence trick|conman]].\n\nNed learned to understand how people think and react, and although impaired by extreme [[near-sightedness]], he was capable of quickly identifying liars, earning himself a high powered position among the gangs of New York.  Physically, he had a strikingly large head.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Asbury, Henry. ''The French Quarter: An Informal History of the New Orleans Underworld''. New York: Alfred A. Knoff, 1936. {{ISBN|1-56025-494-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.trove.net/MACA0001/MACA0001_001391.html Heliotype], showing Lyons in state\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040907093928/http://www.geocities.com/Heartland/Fields/4791/june1884.html The Willimantic Chronicle - Year of 1884], imprisoned at Springfield\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyons, Ned}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Gang members of New York City]]\n[[Category:Escapees from New York (state) detention]]\n[[Category:Criminals from New York City]]\n\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "HannahDohr", "label": "safe", "comment": "added photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ned_Lyons"}
